<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan Submits UN Reform Plans </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 16 (Xinhua) -- United Nations
Secretary-General Kofi Annan today submitted 90-page reform plans
for the world body.
</P>
<P>
The plans were worked out after more than six months of
consultations with member states. But some of the plans still need
to be approved by U.N. government bodies, such as the General
Assembly.
</P>
<P>
Following are highlights of the reform plans:
</P>
<P>
-- DEVELOPMENT FUND: Make at least 200 million U.S. dollars
available for the biennium beginning 2002 for development
activities from savings obtained from the regular budget by
reducing administrative and other overhead costs in the U.N.
Secretariat;
</P>
<P>
-- DEPUTY: Create a Deputy U.N. Secretary-General post,
preferably a woman, to represent the Secretary-General in his
absence from Headquarters, and spearhead efforts to raise
financing for development. The Deputy Secretary-General will also
ensure the coherence of the organization's cross-sectoral
activities;
</P>
<P>
-- CABINET: Establish a cabinet-style structure that would
prevent 27 senior officials reporting directly to Annan. Instead
four managers would take charge of specific areas for peace and
security, humanitarian affairs, development and economic and
social issues. Another four or five managers, including a human
rights official, will join the group. Twelve entities in the main
bureaucracy would be merged into five;
</P>
<P>
-- AID AGENCIES: Six agencies are to be coordinated in two main
groups -- humanitarian affairs and development. But each agency
would maintain its identity. The aim is closer coordination to
make sure common facilities are developed in each country where
more than one agency operates;
</P>
<P>
-- DISARMAMENT: Create a new disarmament department integrating
existing programs and centers in New York to prevent the
proliferation of all types of weapons and control or monitor flow
of arms to conflict areas;
</P>
<P>
-- BUDGET: Propose a no-growth budget. This will be the first
time in a generation that there has been negative growth, in real
terms, in the United Nations budget. Eliminate 1,000 staff posts
and reduce administrative costs by 33 percent. These savings will
be reallocated to development;
</P>
<P>
-- GENERAL ASSEMBLY: The General Assembly will refocus its work
on issues of highest priority and reduce the length of its
sessions. Recommends the 185-nation body streamline its agenda of
165 items and set priorities for its various programs. Member
states should also reduce five intergovernmental bodies into two;
</P>
<P>
-- ALL AGENCIES: Recommend a commission made up of government
ministers for the year 2000 to look at the Byzantine system of
specialized agencies, ranging from semi-autonomous groups to those
completely independent of the Secretary-General, such as the World
Bank;
</P>
<P>
-- REVOLVING FUND: Help solve the cash flow problem by asking
for contributions from member countries for those nations, like
the United States, who are heavily in arrears. Interest would have
to be paid by the borrowers to the lenders.
</P>
<P>
In a statement to the special meeting of the U.N. General
Assembly on Reform today, Annan said that the reforms he was
proposing are "bold reforms."
</P>
<P>
"They are the most extensive and far-reaching reforms in the
fifty-two-year history of our organization," he stressed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
