<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Consumer Inflation Up Slowly in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 16 (Xinhua) -- The Consumer Price Index (CPI)
in the U.S. was up by a seasonally adjusted 0.1 percent in June,
the U.S. Labor Department reported today.
</P>
<P>
It was the same as every other month this year except February
when consumer prices increased 0.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
The report showed that the slow-moving of the U.S. CPI in the
month mainly resulted from the falling energy prices and stable
food prices.
</P>
<P>
In June, energy prices were unchanged following substantial
drops in March, April and May. For the first half of the year,
energy prices fell at an 8.9 percent annual rate after increasing
8.6 percent for all of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Food prices, which rose 0.2 percent in June, increased at just
a 0.9 percent annual rate for the first half after an increase of
4.3 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
U.S. consumer inflation for the first half of this year
increased just 1.4 percent, the best for any first half since
1986. It was markedly lower than the 3.3 percent price increase
for all of last year.
</P>
<P>
Excluding food and energy, the first-half inflation rate was
just 2.4 percent, comparing with a 2.6 percent rate for all of
last year. It was the best for the first six months of any year
since 1965.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that June's good inflation news would set the
stage for U.S. Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan's
semiannual report to Congress next week. Some U.S. congressmen
have criticized Greenspan and his colleagues for raising interest
rates in March but have praised them for refraining from
increasing rates since. 
</P>
</TEXT>
