<HEADLINE> Canada's Mutual Funds Assets Set Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Assets managed in Canadian mutual
funds surged to an all-time high of 188.6 billion U.S. dollars by
the end of June, said reports today.
</P>
<P>
In the first six months of this year, 23.8 billion dollars of
new money flowed into mutual funds, including reinvested
distributions.
</P>
<P>
Net sales for June alone were 2.7 billion dollars, making it
the best June ever, according to figures released by the
Investment Funds Institute of Canada.
</P>
<P>
Net sales for the first six months of the year jumped to 22.2
billion dollars from 15.2 billion dollars for the same period in
1996.
</P>
<P>
"I think the fund industry has a realistic shot at 220 billion
dollars by the end of the year," predicted Dan Richards, president
of Toronto-based consultant Marketing Solutions.
</P>
<P>
"For the first six months of this year, every month except
January was an all-time record," he added.
</P>
<P>
The surge of Canada's mutual funds assets were fueled by rising
stock markets and individuals seeking investment alternatives, the
reports said.
</P>
<P>
The low interest rates here are sending investors into the arms
of the fund industry.
</P>
<P>
"As money is coming due from guaranteed investment certificates
and people need to put it somewhere, mutual funds -- for many
people -- are becoming the only alternative," Richards was quoted
as saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
