<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Inflation Slightly up for June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe's monthly inflation rose
slightly to 21.4 percent in June, according to figures released
today by the Central Statistical Office.
</P>
<P>
Economists warned that Zimbabwe's economy is facing serious
inflationary pressures stemming from on-going wage and salary
negotiations and expected administered price increases. They
predicted the inflation would exceed 24 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Central Statistical Office said that prices rose on average
1.4 percent over the previous month.
</P>
<P>
But the economists warned that the figure could be higher
later in the year following July's wage and salary negotiations
which are likely to see awards of up to 40 percent for workers in
most sectors.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe has over the past few weeks witnessed an upsurge in
strikes as workers demand wages and salary increases of up to 40
percent which they argued, would restore an eroded purchasing
power. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
