<HEADLINE> Canada's Manufacturing Shipments Fall in May </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Canada's total manufacturing
shipments fell for the first time in 1997, edging down 0.2 percent
in May, Statistics Canada reported today.
</P>
<P>
The value of Canadian manufacturing shipments dropped 0.2
percent to 25.9 billion U.S. dollars in May.
</P>
<P>
"May's slight easing follows four consecutive increases, and
reflects both the influence of several moderate declines and the
absence of any strong increases," the federal agency said.
</P>
<P>
Overall, decreases were recorded in 13 of the 22 major industry
groups, which accounted for almost 51 percent of Canada's total
shipments.
</P>
<P>
The most significant decreases in May were recorded in the
primary metal (-2.6 percent) and the refined petroleum and coal
products (-3.4 percent) industries.
</P>
<P>
Yet, these decreases were partly offset by increases in the
motor vehicle (+2.1 percent) and the electrical and electronic
products (+1.7 percent) industries.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, Canadian manufacturers secured a large
increase in their contracts for the third time this year, a
development that bodes well for future shipments.
</P>
<P>
Total unfilled orders shot up 2.4 percent in May to 27.8
billion dollars, as international demand for Canadian aircraft and
parts continued to grow.
</P>
<P>
In May, manufacturers' inventories rose 0.6 percent to 33.6
billion dollars, the fourth consecutive increase after small
declines in December and January. 
</P>
</TEXT>
