<HEADLINE> France to Abandon Majority Stock Holding in Thomson CSF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 16 (Xinhua) -- The state will abandon the majority
stock holding in the Thomson CSF defense-electronics group after
completing its restructuring process, possibly by the end of the
year, said French Minister of Economy and Finance Dominique
Strauss-Kahn today.
</P>
<P>
The French state now holds 58 percent of the stocks of Thomson
CSF, and is looking for a French company to set up an ownership
alliance while selling the remaining part of the stocks.
</P>
<P>
"When one starts from 58 percent and wishes to reach an
alliance with a partner, it is difficult to remain above 50
percent (in stock holding)," Kahn told parliament.
</P>
<P>
The stock value of Thomson CSF fell by 3.6 percent Tuesday, the
first day of its trading after Prime Minister Lionel Jospin
announced the stop of the privatization process of the group last
weekend.
</P>
<P>
The French government said Tuesday that no decision was made on
who the government would ally with for the future running of
Thomson CSF, although the Alcatel Alsthom SA engineering group was
widely expected to be the one to be chosen.
</P>
<P>
Strauss-Kahn said that the state could maintain a 33 percent
ownership of the stocks, although other options are possible.
</P>
<P>
"Nothing is decided in this field. We will launch in the
coming weeks a new procedure and see with different players how
the state can reach its objective," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the government wishes to have a French
partner rather than a European one, a policy different from that
of former Prime Minister Alain Juppe.
</P>
<P>
The stock value of Thomson CSF has fallen by 13.7 percent since
May 26, the day after the leftist coalition led in the first round
of legislative elections. 
</P>
</TEXT>
