<HEADLINE> Manila Revises Inflation Target Due to Peso Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 16 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government has
decided to raise its targeted inflation rate to 8 percent from the
previously-projected 5.2 to 5.7 percent, the governor of the
central bank said today.
</P>
<P>
Central bank chief Gabriel Singson was quoted by the local Sky
Cable television as saying that the inflation target was revised
due to a possible 10 percent price hike triggered by the
devaluation of the Philippine peso.
</P>
<P>
The inflation rate, which stood at 8.4 percent last year,
averaged a low 4.6 percent for the first six months of this year.
</P>
<P>
After the de facto depreciation of the peso last Friday, fears
of price hikes have swept the country. But a government task force
said today there was so far no hikes in prices of basic
commodities.
</P>
<P>
The National Power Corporation said today it will not raise its
power rates in at least two months. But businessmen from other
sectors, including oil and food industries, said they will have to
heave prices due to the sharp depreciation of the peso.
</P>
<P>
The exchange rate of the peso against the U.S. dollar has
depreciated more than 11 percent to 29.35 pesos against one dollar
today, compared to the 26.40 pesos before the central bank's
floatation of the peso last Friday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
