<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Cabinet OKs Participation in Alpha Space </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, July 16 (Xinhua) -- The German government today approved
the country's participation in the international Alpha Space
Station project, the largest one planned worldwide so far.
</P>
<P>
According to the government's decision, Germany would
contribute 2.5 billion marks (1.4 billion U.S. dollars) to the
project, announced German Research Minister Juergen Ruettgers
here today.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the station would be the central area of
German space activities over the coming years.
</P>
<P>
An international agreement on the Alpha Space Station, which is
being built by the United States, Russia, Japan, the European
Union (EU) and Canada, would be signed in autumn this year,
Ruettgers said.
</P>
<P>
The United States plans to bear half of the costs to build the
station, followed by Russia with a share of 30 percent, Japan with
8 percent, the EU with 5 percent and Canada with 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The station is intended for peaceful international space
research and scientific cooperation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
