<HEADLINE> Britain Welcomes European Union's Agenda 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 16 (Xinhua) -- The British government expressed
here today its endorsement to the European Union (EU) executive
Commission's proposals of admitting new EU members, but urged more
radical farm spending cuts.
</P>
<P>
British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook said in a statement issued
here today, "Today's launch by the European Commission of its
Agenda 2000 proposals opens a new chapter in the history of the
European Union."
</P>
<P>
"I welcome the fact that we are moving away from introspection
about our institutions to a new agenda based on the twin aims of
enlargement and policy reform," Cook said. "These are key
components in the new European agenda which the new British
government wants to advance."
</P>
<P>
On the EU's enlargement plan, Cook said, "Enlargement is a
central objective for the UK and the EU. We must grasp this
historical opportunity to enhance security and prosperity
throughout Europe."
</P>
<P>
"We look forward to opening the (entry) negotiations themselves
during the UK's presidency of the EU in the first half of 1998,"
Cook said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on the proposals on the EU Common Agricultural Policy,
which takes a lion's share of the EU budget, Cook said that the
agriculture reform is "a top priority if enlargement is to be
affordable and successful. We want a competitive and viable
European agriculture, friendly to the consumer and the
environment."
</P>
<P>
The foreign secretary noted that although the proposals will
bring real benefits to consumers, the British government will need
a still more radical strategy.
</P>
<P>
"A cap on overall spending must increase the pressure to reduce
agriculture spending which at present takes half of the budget,"
he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
