<HEADLINE> Britain Promises Tough Action on Smuggled Beef </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 16 (Xinhua) -- The British government has promised
the European Union (EU) that it would take tough measures to crack
down on illegal beef exports, but repeated its warning of blocking
beef exports from other EU countries that failed to meet British
standards.
</P>
<P>
British Agriculture Minister Jack Cunningham was quoted by
local press reports as telling the European Parliament's BSE or
mad cow disease committee that "we are totally committed to the
principles of openness and transparency" in fighting against
illegal beef exports.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that some British beef, under the global trade
embargo, had been illegally exported to other countries,
triggering a new wave of hostility across Europe.
</P>
<P>
Cunningham said, "I'm determined to crack down hard on anyone
who runs risks with human safety. We are looking at very
sophisticated criminal fraud that has gone beyond the EU itself."
</P>
<P>
British Prime Minister Tony Blair has reportedly agreed to give
new powers to British enforcement authorities in an effort to put
an end to illegal beef traffic.
</P>
<P>
However, Cunningham confirmed that the new Labor government
would not withdraw an action against the EU's worldwide ban at the
European Court of Justice. He said that "it's going to be an
important test of the legality of the ban," which was imposed in
March 1996.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that Britain expected the rest of the EU
countries to live up to the standards that it had set for British
beef in order to "ensure that imports have been given the same
rigorous treatment on the removal of specified materials." 
</P>
</TEXT>
