<HEADLINE> S.Leonean Delegation to Talk With ECOWAN </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, July 16 (Xinhua) -- A four- man delegation sent by
the Sierra Leonean military junta left here Wednesday for talks
with an ECOWAS mediation commission in Ivory Coast in an attempt
to end the seven week political impasse in Sierra Leone after the
may 25 coup.
</P>
<P>
Leader of the Sierra Leonean delegation, Chief Secretary
of State (prime minister) Solomon Musa said, ''We are going to
put the case for the coup across at last''.
</P>
<P>
" The international community has not given us the opportunity
to air our grievances and they had condemned us outright,'' he
said at the internatiomal airport which is still being held by
Nigerian troops.
</P>
<P>
A group of heavily armed Nigerian soldiers watched the
interview from a distance.
</P>
<P>
According to a foreign ministry official, the junta delegation
will press for the formation of a broad-based government to
involve all key actors in Sierra Leone's politics including
former president Kabbah and rebel leader Foday Ssankoh.
</P>
<P>
The delegatiom will also press for a national comference to be
held in Freetown to work out modalities for general elections.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Sierra Leone's military leader Johnny Paul Koroma
said that his government '' is only here to correct wreckless
situation that was apparently going on during the civilian
regime.''
</P>
<P>
'' The only way out is to give us some time so that we can
correct and straight out the situation in the country. We are
soldiers and we shall be going back to the barracks,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
He went on, ''All we need now is to correct the situation
especially now that we have succeeded in bringing peace to the
country.''
</P>
<P>
He warned, ''Now that peace is at out doorstep. If we allow
it to slip away, we shall never get it again because the rebels
will not go back to the bush. They will stay in Freetown and
shall not go anywhere. '' 
</P>
</TEXT>
