<DOCNO> XIE19970717.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Denies Report on Bosnia SFOR Raid Refusal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 16 (Xinhua) -- France today denied a report by the
U.S. newspaper the New York Times that French troops deployed in
Bosnia refused to carry out a second raid planned by NATO-led
Stabilization Force (SFOR) to arrest Serbian war crime suspects.
</P>
<P>
"This report is devoid of any ground. The French forces in
Bosnia are an integral part of the SFOR, obey the rules of
engagement decided by NATO and follow the instructions of the
command of the force," said French Foreign Ministry spokesman
Jacques Rummelhardt.
</P>
<P>
Quoting unidentified U.S. and French officials, the New York
Times said in its latest issue that France refused to associate
with a new operation against war crime suspects, regarding it as
"too risky."
</P>
<P>
An SFOR operation against Serbian suspects, launched last
Thursday by British and American troops in northwestern Bosnia,
resulted in the death of one Serbian suspect and the arrest of
another.
</P>
<P>
"France has never ceased to stress that the digging-in of the
peace in Bosnia-Herzegovina demands that justice prevail, and this
will pass in particular through the judgment of persons accused of
war crimes," said Rummelhardt.
</P>
<P>
He also said that France was the origin of the idea to set up
the International Criminal Tribunal (TPI) in the Hague to try
Bosnian war criminals.
</P>
<P>
"We have always insisted on the need that the persons accused
by the TPI be arrested and brought to this jurisdiction in the
Hague," said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
The operation last week was launched in Prijedor, which is
located in a region under the command of British troops deployed
in Bosnia, while most of Serbian war crime suspects are holding
out in Pale, in a region under the command of French SFOR troops.
</P>
<P>
France said that the operation launched last week by British
troops was "legitimate and fully in conformity with the mandate of
the SFOR," but it prefers that the operation to arrest war
criminals be carried out by Bosnians themselves. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
