<DOCNO> XIE19970717.0015 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Come to Britain for Quality, Added Value: Beckett </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 16 (Xinhua) -- A campaign, to ensure Britain is
the preferred location for inward investors, was spelt out today
by President of the Board of Trade Margaret Beckett.
</P>
<P>
Foreign direct investment in Britain soared 24 percent last
year to a record 9.34 billion pounds (14.9 billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the launch of the Invest in Britain Bureau's (IBB)
Annual Review of Operations 1997, Beckett said, "The key to many
investment decisions has been the creation of partnerships between
business, investment agencies, local and national government."
</P>
<P>
"Our aim now is to ensure that attractive conditions are
maintained and such partnerships developed further so that Britain
can meet the very real challenges that lie ahead in competing for
investment on the world stage," she added.
</P>
<P>
IBB's Annual Review of Operations 1997 revealed a record 483
projects during 1996/97. These created 46,179 jobs and safeguarded
a further 47,545 jobs.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 70 projects were foreign acquisitions. US, German and
Japanese firms committed billions of pounds between them to the
automotive industry -- both motor manufacturing and component
suppliers.
</P>
<P>
World-class companies have continued to invest in British
utilities, while trans-Atlantic and Far Eastern firms alike looked
to the UK to establish their European headquarters.
</P>
<P>
The US remains the single biggest source of foreign direct
investment in Britain. US companies accounted for investment worth
3.9 billion pounds (6.24 billion US dollars) -- 43 percent of the
total.
</P>
<P>
Beckett also outlined four key areas -- economic stability,
skills, Europe and competitiveness -- where the UK can help create
a business environment within which firms will want to work, and
underlined the importance of partnership in promoting Britain in
the global market for inward investment.
</P>
<P>
Expressing her confidence in the competitive world, she said,
"Britain is rightly proud of its record in attracting inward
investment from around the world and we have good reason to be
confident about the future." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
