<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southern African Bio-medical Meeting Opens in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 16 (Xinhua) -- The Bio-Medical Research and
Training Institute (BRTI) meeting began here today, stressing the
importance of action-oriented research in the improvement of
the health sectors in the southern African countries.
</P>
<P>
BRTI, which aims to collaborate with institutes and
laboratories in the Southern African Development Community
(SADC), is a regional research and training institute formed two
years ago to spearhead a common approach to the region's health
problems.
</P>
<P>
More than 25 representatives from SADC ministries of health,
research institutes and universities from Denmark, Switzerland,
Nertherlands, Tanzania, the United States and the United Kingdom
attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
BRTI board Chairman Stephen Chandiwana said decision making by
policy makers needed to be backed by accurate information,
especially in this era where most African governments were faced
by a serious shortage of resources.
</P>
<P>
He said, ''At another level, health managers and workers need
to carry out simple operational research to improve programatic
performance, hence the need to include all actors in health and
health-related research.''
</P>
<P>
He revealed that of the 30 billion U.S.Dollars investment in
health worldwide, oniy 1.6 billion dollars or five percent, was
earmarked for health in developing countries and only 150 million
dollars or 0.1 percent was used for direct support of research
activities in developing countries.
</P>
<P>
''The provision of a centre where established scientists can
conduct high quality, relevant research is essential, if Africa
is to retain and develop its scientific resources,'' he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Chandiwana called for financial assistance to promoe active
research in bio-medicine in sub-Saharan Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
