<HEADLINE> Israel Strongly Denounces UN Resolution on Settlements </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Israel strongly denounced the
resolution adopted by the United Nations (UN) General Assembly
overnight which called for sanctions against Israel's settlement
activities.
</P>
<P>
The Assembly passed the non-binding resolution in a vote of
131 in favor, 3 against, with 14 abstentions. It condemned
Israel for failing to comply with the earlier resolution
adopted by the Assembly in April which called for an halt
to the building of Har Homa settlement in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The resolution called on U.N. members to actively discourage
activities that contribute to the Jewish settlements, while
demanding Israel provide information on the goods produced by
its settlements.
</P>
<P>
In his reaction, Israeli Prime Minister Binjamin Netanyahu
criticized the U.N. for dealing with the issues of "building
housing for youth couples in Israel's capital city" when
there are wars and hunger in other places of the world.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister David Levy denounced the U.N. resolution for
contradicting the peace process and creating unnecessary tensions
in the region. He called for an end to what he dubbed as
"an ugly game to try to isolate and accuse Israel" in the
U.N..
</P>
<P>
Levy paid tributes to the United States and Micronesia, the
only two states voted against the resolution together with
Israel. He also called for a code of behavior in
Israeli-Palestinian negotiations, saying the two sides should
solve the differences through direct negotiations rather than
bringing them to the international arena.
</P>
<P>
This was the third resolution passed by the U.N. General
Assembly to condemn the building of Har Homa settlement since
Israel started the construction in March. The Israeli-Palestinian
peace negotiations have been frozen since then, leading to a
rising tension and escalating violence between the two sides.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
