<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan Announces Exports-Oriented Trade Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan announced here today an
export-oriented trade policy for 1997-98 fiscal year, which
envisages substantial incentives to encourage export of
value-added products.
</P>
<P>
Commerce Minister Ishaq Dar unveiled the trade policy this
evening on radio and television, saying the policy is projected to
reduce the trade gap to 2.33 billion U.S. dollars during the
current fiscal year from 3.3 billion dollars in 1996-97 fiscal
year.
</P>
<P>
The export and import targets for the current fiscal year are
set at 9.57 billion dollars and 11.90 billion dollars
respectively.
</P>
<P>
"It is expected that the best use of incentives and concessions
provided by the government will enhance exports and increase
earnings of much needed foreign exchange for Pakistan," Dar said.
</P>
<P>
Under the policy exports of all items excluding kitchen items
will be allowed via land routes to Afghanistan and the Central
Asian republics at market prices on filing of regular shipping
bills, without the facility of duty drawback.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, a few new items, mostly industrial raw materials,
are also being allowed for import from India, said the minister.
</P>
<P>
Dar said 50 percent of the admissible duty drawbacks will be
paid within three days of the presentation of complete documents
by exporters to the customs authorities and the balance will be
paid after verification of the claims.
</P>
<P>
Customs duty will be reduced on wet blue hides from 5 percent
to zero percent. Import duty on finished and patent leather will
be reduced from 45 percent to 15 percent, he added.
</P>
<P>
Local assemblers and manufacturers of automotive vehicles and
components will be allowed to import duty-free assembly kits
corresponding to the number of their exported units provided no
duty drawbacks were claimed by them at the time of exports.
</P>
<P>
Imports of certain items, machines, tools and equipment
required by gems and jewelry industry have been allowed duty free
to manufacturers and exporters, according to the minister.
</P>
<P>
Dar said export refinance for computer software exports will be
provided up to 100 percent of export contract value for 180 days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
