<HEADLINE> Chinese Experts: Absurd Historical Views Aim to Disrupt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Four prominent Chinese experts on
international relations have attacked the absurd historical views
of Japanese right-wing groups which are intended to disrupt
Sino-Japanese relations. They gave their views in an interview to
be published by China's Guang Ming Daily newspaper on Thursday.
The following are extracts from the article:
</P>
<P>
Fang Lianqing, vice president of the International Relations
Institute attached to Beijing University, said a small right-wing
force has always existed in Japan and has disrupted the healthy
development of Sino-Japanese relations.
</P>
<P>
They have published a number of books in recent years to
eulogize the history of Japan's invasion of other Asian nations
including China.
</P>
<P>
One of the books, running to hundreds of thousands words, a
summary of the so-called "Great East Asia War," surprisingly
attempted to reverse the verdict on Japanese aggression.
</P>
<P>
Those kinds of books whitewashed the invasive nature of the war
launched by Japan, glorifying the bloody history of Japan's
invasion and justifying the actions of Japanese fascist war
criminals.
</P>
<P>
Luo Weilong, deputy chairman of the China Society for the Study
of Japanology, said that those right-wing figures not only
vilified the Japanese politicians who faced up to and admitted the
correct view of history, but also condemned the media and
education circles who told the truth, complaining that Japan was
trapped by a "syndrome of national self-maltreatment" and a
"syndrome of historical self-maltreatment."
</P>
<P>
Jiang Daonai, secretary general of China's Society for the
History of Sino-Japanese Relations, said that those right-wing
figures were advocating Japanese people to restore "the national
spirit" of the Japanese nation and to reestablish the so-called
"correct Japanese outlook of history."
</P>
<P>
Liu Jiangyong, a research fellow with the Institute for the
Study of Modern International Relations, said that after several
decades of economic development, Japan has become a major
economic power in the world over the past few years. With this, a
sense of national pride has begun to take root in the minds of a
number of Japanese people.
</P>
<P>
Under such conditions, a handful of Japanese right-wing figures
have taken advantage of the change in attitude of Japanese people,
seeking to mislead the younger generation and national sentiment
and to disrupt Japan's peaceful development and the main trend in
Sino-Japanese relations.
</P>
<P>
When asked about the facts of the Marco Polo Bridge Incident
and the Rape of Nanjing (Nanking), Luo Weilong strongly criticized
those right-wing figures for distorting history by claiming that,
"the Marco Polo Bridge Incident was created by the Chinese side;
Chinese troops opened fire first; Japan had no plan to invade
China; the death toll in the Rape of Nanjing (Nanking) was
recklessly concocted." More
nnnn
</P>
</TEXT>
