<HEADLINE> UK Launches Internet Site to Promote Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 16 (Xinhua) -- A 40,000 page Internet site went
live in Britain today, providing the 50 million Internet users all
over the world with detailed information on traveling in the UK.
</P>
<P>
The site, www.visitbritain.com, was built by the British
Tourist Authority (BTA) with the aim of promoting the country's
booming tourist industry.
</P>
<P>
Britain's Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sports
Chris Smith welcomed the launching of the project, saying that
"tourists from Britain and overseas increasingly wish to travel
independently. I welcome this use of new technology to give people
all over the world easier access to the information they need."
</P>
<P>
The site offers tourists a vast database of attractions, events
and accommodation in England, Scotland and Wales by displaying
picture-postcard style images of the UK's coasts, cities and
countryside as well as detailed maps and information about its
changeable climate.
</P>
<P>
The BTA intends to build links between the site and central
hotel reservation systems to allow Internet users to book hotel
rooms easily.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the site will also carry advertising, and British
Airways has already signed up as the first customer.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that tourism is now one of the top five
industries in Britain, worth an annual 40 billion pounds (67.1
billion US dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
