<HEADLINE> 2 Killed, 6 Wounded by PKK in Southeastern Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Turkey's outlawed Kurdish Workers'
Party (PKK) killed two people and wounded six others in an armed
attack on a village in southeastern Turkey Tuesday night, the
semi-official Anatolia news agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
The agency said that a group of PKK militants raided Gurkavak
village in Yuksekova town of Hakkari province bordering Iran and
exchanged fire with village guards at 24:00 p.m. local time (2100
GMT).
</P>
<P>
The PKK guerrillas threw grenades at a house in the village,
leaving two people in the house dead and six children wounded, the
agency said.
</P>
<P>
It added that the clash between the PKK rebels and the village
guards continued until early this morning.
</P>
<P>
The militants set a house on fire and escaped later, according
to the report.
</P>
<P>
The PKK has been fighting a separatist war for autonomy since
August 1984 which has claimed over 27,000 lives in eastern and
southeastern Turkey. 
</P>
