<HEADLINE> Chinese Experts: Absurd Historical Views Aim to Disrupt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Fang Lianqing said that history cannot be distorted.
</P>
<P>
Japanese troops, after launching the September 18 Incident and
annexing the three northeastern provinces, conspired to invade
northern China and wage an all-out war against China.
</P>
<P>
The Hiroda cabinet convened a meeting attended by five
ministers in 1936 and worked out an invasion plan to occupy
northern China and Shanghai first and then other parts of China.
</P>
<P>
After the meeting, Japanese forces began to invade northern
China through Shanhaiguan, a strategic pass connecting
northeastern and northern China.
</P>
<P>
The then First Head of the Japanese Army's Chief of General
Staff Yshihara admitted that the invasion of northern China led
directly to the Marco Polo Bridge Incident.
</P>
<P>
In 1994, the regimental commander of Japan's troops of
aggression at the time, Muda, confessed, "It was me who fired the
first shot near the Marco Polo Bridge which set off the war.
That's why I think I should take responsibility for the war."
</P>
<P>
Liu Yongjiang said the archcriminal of the Rape of Nanjing,
the Commander of Japan's troops in eastern China, Matsui, wrote in
the Outline to Conquer Nanjing City that "Occupying Nanjing is
intended to force China to surrender."
</P>
<P>
Luo Weilong quoted a report by a New York Times' correspondent
as saying he witnessed three massacres of captives within a few
hours.
</P>
<P>
Three reporters with the Domei News Service, who entered
Nanjing three days after Japanese troops conquered the city, wrote
in their dispatches that they saw 2,000-3,000 charred bodies along
the river bank from Xiaguan to Caoxiexia, and that, ordered by
officers, Japanese troops stabbed Chinese captives to death one by
one as target practice for bayonet fighting and threw their bodies
into air-raid shelters. More
