<HEADLINE> Jordanian Government Ready for Dialogue with </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, July 16 (Xinhua) - Jordanian Prime Minister Abdul Salam
Majali said today that government is ready to have dialogue with
all parties across the political spectrum.
</P>
<P>
Majali made the statement following the Muslim Brotherhood's
threat to boycott of the upcoming parliamentary elections.
</P>
<P>
All the political parties should put forth their vision of how
to conduct the elections in the best way ahead of future meetings
between the government and the parties including the opposition,
said Majali while meeting the director general of the Jordan
Unionist Democratic Party, Assen Danett, according to Radio Jordan.
</P>
<P>
The director general told the press later that today`s meeting
was in the government line to consolidate dialogue with the
political parties.
</P>
<P>
He added that he welcomed the prime minister`s call for
dialogue with all the parties and he urged those parties to
respond.
</P>
<P>
The Muslim Brotherhood, a major opposition party in Jordan,
declared its boycott of the elections earlier last week.
</P>
<P>
The general supervisor of the party Abdul Majeed Thneibat
said Saturday that the Press and Publication Law, the
one-person-one-vote election system, the normalization of ties
with Israel and "the government`s measures to marginalize
political parties" were the main reasons behind the movement`s
decision to boycott the 1997 general elections.
</P>
<P>
Other opposition parties, including the biggest one the
Islamic Action Front, are also considering to go after the
Muslim Brotherhood.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian government Tuesday made the first official
response to the boycott with a statement saying that the
government was to hold free and fair parliamentary elections as
scheduled in November with or without the participation of the
opposition. 
</P>
