<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Heat Wave Hitting New York City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, July 16 (Xinhua) -- The New York area's first heat
wave of the summer began Tuesday with 41 people taken to hospitals
in the city for heat-related problems, including difficult
breathing.
</P>
<P>
The temperature hit 97 degrees in Central Park, and 115 degrees
were registered at midday Tuesday in the crown of the Statue of
Liberty, which forced the National Park Service to shut down the
entire monument to visitors.
</P>
<P>
Tuesday was the beginning of the city's first official heat
wave of the year, as far as the National Weather Service was
concerned. The agency defines a heat wave as three consecutive
days with temperatures of 90 degrees or higher. Tuesday followed a
94-degree high in Central Park Monday and a 92-degree day there
Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The city's reservoirs were about 87 percent full Monday, when
normal volume for this time of year is 94 percent. Electricity
shortages were also reported in some areas of the city. 
</P>
</TEXT>
