<HEADLINE> Chinese Experts: Absurd Historical Views Aim to Disrupt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
On certain incidents of aggression provoked by Japan, Liu
Jiangyong said there are plenty of facts to illustrate that the
"September 18 Incident" in 1931, the "Marco Polo Bridge Incident"
in 1937 and the following all-out war of aggression against China
were all premediated and elaborately planned by the Japanese
militarists.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of the frequent attempts by some Japanese
right-wingers to seek a lawful "basis" for the Japanese
aggression, Liu said that these people, who claimed that "the
definition of aggression is not fixed," denied the existence of
the word of "aggression."
</P>
<P>
These people went so far as to claim that the English word
"aggression" meant "attack" rather than "capture" and thus could
not be categorized as a crime in terms of the international law,
said Liu.
</P>
<P>
Indeed, the meaning of "aggression" illustrated by Kojigen, an
authoritative Japanese dictionary cannot be clearer: "What is
called aggression means invasion into another country and capture
its land," said Liu.
</P>
<P>
The Dictionary on International Law compiled by the Japanese
Institute of International Law says, "Aggression generally refers
to the aim and act of one country to attempt to realize the claim
on another country by means of force so as to change the
situation." More
nnnn
</P>
</TEXT>
