<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNDP Head Praises Annan's Reform Proposals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 16 (Xinhua) -- James Gustave Speth,
administrator of the United Nations Development Program, today
praised the bold reform plans proposed by U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan.
</P>
<P>
"I strongly support the Secretary-General's initiatives because
they will strengthen and streamline the U.N. on every front --
peace and security, human rights, development cooperation,
humanitarian affairs and economic and social affairs," Speth said.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the special meeting of the U.N. General Assembly
early this morning, Annan said that his reform recommendations
were "the most extensive and far-reaching" ones since the world
body was founded 52 years ago.
</P>
<P>
Among his many innovative actions, Annan established the United
Nations Development Group (UNDG) which will be composed of U.N.
funds and programs engaged in development cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Building on existing arrangements, the UNDG will ensure greater
coordination and policy coherence among U.N. development agencies.
It will also strengthen their ability to deliver high-quality
assistance without compromising the identities of the
organizations in the UNDG framework.
</P>
<P>
Most of the U.N.'s financial resources are dedicated to
assisting the poor. Through programs in more than 150 countries,
the U.N. provideds about 3 billions U.S. dollars a year in
development assistance and another 3 billions U.S. dollars in
humanitarian aid.
</P>
<P>
"The United Nations has a track record second to none in
promoting sustainable and equitable development," Speth said.
"This record provides the most compelling case for strengthening
the UN in the economic, social and environmental area -- and the
reforms put forward by the Secretary-General will help achieve
this goal." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
