<HEADLINE> Export-led Growth, Corner Stone of Pak Economic Policy: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Commerce Minister
Muhammad Ishaq Dar said here today that export-led growth is the
corner stone of the government's economic strategy.
</P>
<P>
To lay the foundation for robust outward-oriented economy, it
is now imperative to reverse the anti-export bias in the economic
structure evolved over the last fifty years, Dar said when
unveiling an export-friendly trade policy for the 1997-1998 fiscal
year.
</P>
<P>
The government, he said, is placing special emphasis on the
development of non-traditional items and introduction of Pakistani
products in new markets, including computer software, industrial
designing, engineering goods and furniture.
</P>
<P>
To facilitate smooth flow of exports, it is imperative that all
formalities related to exports should be completed in minimum
possible time, he said.
</P>
<P>
The government already commissioned an export terminal at
Karachi, which provides this facility to exporters under one roof,
he added.
</P>
<P>
In keeping with the government's commitment to an outward
looking dynamic approach to economic issues, the trade policy for
1997-98 is a reflection of this objective, the commerce minister
noted.
</P>
<P>
The measures being initiated through the trade policy will add
to the incentives already announced by the government in the prime
minister's economic revival package and the federal budget, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to decisions taken to facilitate export-related
activities, he said, freight subsidies will continue to be
available on the export of fruits and vegetables only.
</P>
<P>
Private sector will be allowed and supported by the government
on "build, own and operate" (BOO) basis to construct
infrastructure including airports, roads, storage and packaging
facilities, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
