<HEADLINE> Lebanon Sees US Ties with Arab States in Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Foreign Minister Farez
Boueiz said here today that relations between the United
States and Arab states are in crisis due to a shift of
Washington's policy in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Milhem Karam, chairman of the Lebanese
Press Syndicate, the foreign minister said that the
administration of President Bill Clinton has withdrawn from its
role as a "pushing power" in the Middle East peace process
after the Israeli government asked it to do so.
</P>
<P>
"Today it seems that after Israel asked the U.S. to
freeze its activities, the U.S. has retreated from the principle
of pushing power," Boueiz told Karam. "And it seems that
interests of the U.S. with Israel have overpassed its
international role."
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that Washington has shifted from its previous
firm position toward settlements in West Bank and Gaza strip,
with the evidence of the veto it used against U.N. resolutions
condemning Israel's refusal to stop building Jewish settlements
in occupied territories.
</P>
<P>
Among 148 countries voting in the General Assembly Tuesday
night, the U.S., Israel and Micronesia were the only three
countries voted against the resolution, which urges U.N. member
states to "actively discourage" settlement-building activities. 14
countries abstained in the vote.
</P>
<P>
The decision taken by the U.S. congress last month
recognizing Jerusalem as Israel's capital and asking the
administration to move the American embassy to the city from
Tel Aviv was another evidence indicating the change in
Washington's policy, the Lebanese minister noted.
</P>
<P>
"As a result of these upsetting steps, the United States has
gone out of the principles of the peace process which had been
agreed upon, in an addition to retracting its guarantees related
to definite messages on the Israeli withdrawals (from occupied
Arab lands)," the foreign minister said.
</P>
<P>
"Because of these reasons, the relations between the United
States and all the Arab states has begun passing through a
crisis," Boueiz added.
</P>
<P>
"There is a scathing blame on the United states for its
failure to exert pressure on (Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin)
Netanyahu or use its influence to draw him back to the
peace process and the Madrid principles despite it knows
Netanyahu's negativity," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese foreign minister also criticized U.S. Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright because since her appointment she
has not paid a single visit to the region, nor conducted
more contacts, in order to get a knowledge on the "thorny"
situation in the Middle East. 
</P>
</TEXT>
