<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Experts: Absurd Historical Views Aim to Disrupt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
When asked about whether Japan's view of history will affect
Sino-Japanese friendship, Jiang Daoding said how to view Japanese
militarists' war of aggression against China is a matter of
principle and is directly related to the political foundation for
Sino-Japanese relations.
</P>
<P>
Fang Lianqing said some Japanese politicians have frequently
made indiscreet remarks about historical events. This has grown
into a trend formed by absurd historical views in Japan, and if
unchecked, would obstruct the development of bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
Developing friendly relations between China and Japan is of
vital strategic importance to both countries. In fact, the
significance of Sino-Japanese relations has gone beyond a
bilateral level, Luo Weilong noted.
</P>
<P>
He said that the stability or otherwise of bilateral relations
would have implications not only for Japan but also the
Asia-Pacific region and even the whole world.
</P>
<P>
On the question of whether the key to the development of
bilateral relations is Japan's adoption of a correct view of
history, Liu Jiangyong said that taking a correct historical view
has become important not only for Japan's future development but
also for maintaining the hard-won friendship between China and
Japan.
</P>
<P>
Jiang Daoding noted that it was rare in world history that
there were so many conflicting views of a period of history only
50 years previously within Japan's political, media and academic
circles.
</P>
<P>
But how could the Japanese look toward the future in a
scientific and reasonable way if they were even unable to forge a
basic consensus on their own history based on facts, Jiang Daoding
asked.
</P>
<P>
Liu Jiangyong said China will not conclude that Japan is
advocating militarism simply from the remarks and activities of a
small right-wing force in the country.
</P>
<P>
China understands that the Japanese people in general are
peace-loving and the Japanese government tolerates no revival of
militarism. Hereby, we would like to advise those in Japan who
are farsighted enough to pay due attention to the destructive and
dangerous nature of these absurd historical views, and to
consciously resist these views, Liu Jiangyong added.
</P>
<P>
He said the younger generation should be educated to understand
past and present Sino-Japanese relations and form a correct view
of history. 
</P>
</TEXT>
