<DOCNO> XIE19970717.0047 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan's Reform on UN leadership, Management </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 16 (Xinhua) -- United Nations
Secretary-General Kofi Annan today announced before the United
Nations General Assembly his recommendations for the most
extensive and far-reaching reform of the United Nations since it
was founded 52 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The Secretary-General's recommendations are embodied in a
report titled "Renewing the United Nations: A Program for Reform,"
in response to the need of the United Nations to deliver more and
better services at less cost. The recommendations also respond to
member states' increasing development, and peacekeeping and
humanitarian needs anticipated for the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
On reform of the leadership and management of the United
Nations, the Secretary-General proposed the following:
</P>
<P>
The Secretary-General proposes to set up a cabinet-style
management entity, to be called the "Senior Management Group,"
consisting of eight or nine senior officials and acting as a
decision-making and policy-making body;
</P>
<P>
The Secretary-General proposes the creation of a post of Deputy
Secretary-General to act in the Secretary-Genenal's absence, to
share his representational duties and to link actions and policies
that cut across administrative and sectoral boundaries;
</P>
<P>
The Secretary-General recommends that the General Assembly
review its agenda which currently consist of over 160 agenda
items appearing annually and retire agenda items that are no
longer of high priorities and review the agenda periodically for
further adoption to current needs;
</P>
<P>
The Secretary-General recommends that the General Assembly
periodically focus its discussion for a concentrated period of
time on major issues of international importance such as financing
for development. Such focus will encourage participation at the
highest level by ministers and heads of states;
</P>
<P>
The reform proposals also recommend shorting the session of
the General Assembly by three weeks from about 15 weeks to
about 12;
</P>
<P>
The Secretary-General recommends to the General Assembly that
whenever it adopts a new program requiring significant staffing
and financing commitment, the program should include a sunset
provision;
</P>
<P>
Finally the Secretary-General recommends the adoption of a
results-based budgeting system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
