<HEADLINE> Cyprus President on Bi-Communal Direct Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Cypriot President Glafcos Clerides
said here today that the U.N.-led direct talks in the U.S. was
held in a very good atmosphere but no progress was made in solving
the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
Speaking upon his return from a ten-day visit to the U.S. and
Britain, where he attended direct talks between the Greek and
Turkish Cypriot sides and had a meeting with British Prime
Minister Tony Blair, President Clerides noted, however, that he
"did not expect any developments on Cyprus issue as it is still
too early".
</P>
<P>
"A process has started and is continuing", he said,
pointing out that "progress will occur when the gap between
the positions held by the two sides is bridged."
</P>
<P>
The President explained that the U.N. Secretary General's
Special Advisor on Cyprus, Diego Cordovez, who coordinated the
talks in Troutbeck, prepared a non-paper that will become a
paper if the two sides agree to it.
</P>
<P>
The two sides, he said, will study the non-paper and then
express their positions.
</P>
<P>
President Clerides also referred to his proposal for a
meeting with Denktash in Nicosia, under the auspices of U.N.
Resident Representative, Gustave Feissel, in order to discuss
humanitarian issues, especially that of persons missing since the
Turkish occupation of the north in 1974.
</P>
<P>
There is no agenda for the Nicosia meeting, the President
said, adding that humanitarian issues, including that of Greek
Cypriot enclaved in the northern Turkish-controlled part of the
island, were also discussed in Troutbeck.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided since 1974 when Turkish troops took
over the northern third of the island following a failed coup
by Greek Cypriots allied with the military junta that ruled
Greece at the time. 
</P>
