<HEADLINE> Slovenian PM Upbeat About Chances to Join EU </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Slovenia apparently sees its chances
to join the European Union (EU) improved after acquiring assurance
from German Chancellor Helmut Kohl today that Germany will firmly
support Slovenia's membership bid.
</P>
<P>
Slovenian Prime Minister Janez Drnovsek told the German news
agency DPA after a meeting with Kohl today in Bonn that he was
pleased with Bonn's suggestion that the EU admit new members
individually, and not in groups as was the case in 1995 when it
took in Austria, Finland and Sweden.
</P>
<P>
"If Slovenia is treated individually, we think that we will
have much better chances," he said.
</P>
<P>
Drnovsek's visit to Bonn came as the EU announced in Strasbourg
today that Slovenia and five other European nations had been
selected as new member candidates with which it will begin
accession negotiations early next year.
</P>
<P>
Despite some analysts' belief that the EU is unlikely to admit
new members until after 2002, Drnovsek said, "I still think
Slovenia could become a (EU) member by 2001 or at least 2002."
</P>
<P>
According to German government spokesman Peter Hausmann, Kohl
told Drnovsek that Germany firmly supported Slovenia's bid to join
the EU, and that the decision made by the EU in Strasbourg was a
recognition of Slovenia's progress in democratic and economic
reforms.
</P>
<P>
Slovenia was excluded earlier this month from making the first
wave to join the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO). At the
insistence of the United States, the NATO summit in Madrid on July
8-9 only selected Poland, Hungary and the Czech Republic to join
the Western alliance in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Kohl told Drnovsek that Germany had "great sympathy" for
Slovenia's wish for a speedy admission into NATO and supported the
country's efforts to this end.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the NATO summit had made clear that the door
would remain open to admit further new members and it had also
given special emphasis on the positive development in Slovenia.
</P>
<P>
Since Slovenia's NATO bid was turned down in Madrid, some
Slovenian opposition leaders have reportedly accused the
government of relying too much on the backing of France and Italy
and not enlisting sufficient support from Bonn. 
</P>
</TEXT>
