<DOCNO> XIE19970717.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan's Reform Proposals on UN Structure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 16 (Xinhua) -- United Nations
Secretary-General Kofi Annan announced today before the General
Assembly his recommendations for the most extensive and
far-reaching reform of the U.N. since it was founded 52 years ago.
</P>
<P>
On reforming the structure of the United Nations, the
Secretary-General proposes the following:
</P>
<P>
The budget for 1998-1999 presented to the General Assembly
implements the cutting of 1,000 secretariat posts;
</P>
<P>
Three United Nations departments in economic and social affairs
at the secretariat are being integrated into one new department,
achieving significant greater unity of purpose and the coherence
of efforts;
</P>
<P>
United Nations programs in fighting crimes, drug trafficking,
money laundering and terrorism are to be combined in Vienna, under
one administrator, Senator Arlacchi of Italy, who is a specialist
on organized crime;
</P>
<P>
The center for human rights and the Office of the High
Commissioner for Human Rights are bing consolidated into one
office headed by Mary Robinson, currently president of Ireland, as
the new High Commissioner;
</P>
<P>
Three separate entities of the United Nations secretariat that
assist intergovernmental bodies to run meetings are being
consolidated into one support service department.
</P>
<P>
The Secretary-General is initiating a move towards setting up
common facilities and support services in the 134 countries where
the United Nations has activities and provides services.
Significant saving should derive from the consolidation of
programs and agencies of administration in each country.
</P>
<P>
In the development field, various entities, including the
United Nations Children's fund and the United Nations Development
Program, are encouraged to develop a similar policy framework that
they will all utilize as a common starting point for their
specific programs.
</P>
<P>
The Secretary-General calls for simplification of United
Nations personnel and administrative rules.
</P>
<P>
Significant reductions in United Nations paperwork will be
sustained. Current projections for 1997 show that the United
Nations has reduced paper by 30 percent over 1995 use rates.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
