<HEADLINE> Liberian Presidential Campaign Ends Tomorrow: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FREETOWN, July 16 (Xinhua) - Campaign in Liberia's
presidential and parliamental elections which was due on Saturday
or July 19 will end tomorrow, a Liberian election official in
Monrovia told Xinhua today in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
"The campaign so far has been trouble free and we hope the
trend will continue," he said.
</P>
<P>
Political analysts said the election in which over 1.5 million
Liberians are expected to vote, will involve all political
parties and presidential aspirants.
</P>
<P>
The most notable will be Charles Taylor, leader of the
National Patriotic Council (NPC), Ellen Johnson-Sirleaf, leader
of the Unity Party, George Boley of the National Democratic Party
and Al-Haji Kromah of the United Liberation Movement of Liberia
for Democracy (UNLIMO-K).
</P>
<P>
Taylor, who would climax his campaign on Thursday has been
tipped as the winner when the campaign started. However, he has
been on the slide during the past three weeks with
Johnson-Sirleaf and Kromah gaining some leads, election observers
said.
</P>
<P>
Kromah is already crying foul as he claimed in an interview
with Xinhua that some 500,000 of his supporters who are refugees
in neighboring Guinea have been stopped at the border from
entering the country to vote.
</P>
<P>
Kromah who carries his campaign like an American presidential
election boasted, "No matter what they do, I am certain to win."
</P>
<P>
U.N. election observers are already in Monrovia and will be
joined by human rights groups by Friday to monitor the polls.
</P>
<P>
The election is being supervised by the west African
peace-keeping troops Known as ECOMOG, which has brokered peace in
Liberia for the past seven years.
</P>
<P>
A new FM radio station funded by the United States government
was launched in Monrovia today to provide "unbiased news coverage
for voters in Saturday 's election.
</P>
<P>
Over 150,000 Liberians died in the rebel war with about a
million fleeing to other countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
