<HEADLINE> Egypt Lauds UN Resolution Condemning Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Egypt today hailed a UN General
Assembly resolution condemning Israel's Jewish expansionist policy
and requesting its members to halt support for Jewish settlements.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday the UN General Assembly for the third time voted
overwhelmingly to condemn Israel for the construction of a Jewish
neighborhood in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
In a statement to reporters today, Assistant Foreign Minister
Sayed Qasim said the resolution is very significant because it won
the support of 131 countries across the the world.
</P>
<P>
Only Israel, the U.S. and Micronesia Islands voted against the
resolution.
</P>
<P>
"What is important in the resolution is that it urges member
countries not to encourage activities contributing to the
development of settlements," Qasim added.
</P>
<P>
The resolution, tabled by 15 Arab and Muslim countries, called
for an end of foreign aid to Jewish settlements in the West Bank
and Gaza and a ban on the import of goods produced there.
</P>
<P>
Although the resolution was non-binding, Arab and Muslim
countries considered it an important step in keeping up
international pressure against Israel's decision to go ahead with
a new Jewish housing project in East Jerusalem, which the
Palestinians want as their future capital.
</P>
<P>
The resolution followed up a recent report by UN
Secretary-General Kofi Annan confirming Israel's failure to stop
the Har Homa construction, a project that has paralyzed
Israeli-Palestinian peacemaking efforts and fueled violence in the
occupied Palestinian territories.
</P>
<P>
The United States has used its veto right in the Security
Council twice to block UN resolutions against the Israeli project.
</P>
<P>
In Tel Aviv, meanwhile, the resolution met with fierce attack
from Israeli Prime Minister Binjamin Netanyahu. 
</P>
</TEXT>
