<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: West, Russia Remain Different on NATO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Western high officials flew to
Moscow one after another recently to allay Russia's concern after
NATO's Madrid summit held on July 8-9, that took a decision to
invite Poland, the Czech Republic and Hungary to the military
alliance.
</P>
<P>
At the Madrid summit, NATO leaders also considered the
possibility of the Baltic states joining the alliance. These
actions, naturally, provoked Russia's dissatisfaction.
</P>
<P>
While reiterating its strong objection to the move, the Russian
leaders voiced their readiness to improve relations with
Lithuania, Latvia and Estonia. To Russia, dialogue seems better
than confrontation.
</P>
<P>
First of all, Russian President Boris Yeltsin invited Finnish
President Martti Ahtisaari to the northern resort of Shuiskaya
Chupa in Karelia, where Yeltsin is holidaying, to "spend the
weekend together," combining recreation with discussion of
bilateral and international matters.
</P>
<P>
The topic of conversation between the two presidents was NATO's
promise that its door remains open to membership by the Baltic
states of Estonia, Latvia and Lithuania -- former Soviet republics
that Russia has insisted must remain outside the alliance.
</P>
<P>
Before Ahtisaari's departure, Yeltsin once again said that "we
will categorically oppose that," regarding NATO's invitation of
the Baltics as "dangerous."
</P>
<P>
For his part, the Finnish president said, "Each country can
resolve problems of its security on its own."
</P>
<P>
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright arrived in St.
Petersburg last Saturday, and had three-hour talks with Russian
Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov.
</P>
<P>
The two sides agreed to speed up the modification of the Treaty
of Conventional Forces in Europe, to make joint efforts to promote
the Middle East peace process, and to consistently encourage the
implementation of the Dayton agreement in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
However, Russia and the U.S. remained different over the Baltic
states. Primakov said that Russia opposes the Baltic states'
admission to NATO, and emphasized "the Russian position does not
change depending on momentary interests."
</P>
<P>
The Russian foreign minister noted a system guaranteeing the
Baltic states' security, independence and sovereignty must be
created. "Such a system might be based on Russia's guarantees, or
on joint guarantees," he added.
</P>
<P>
In response to the question voiced by Primakov, Albright, who
was visiting in Vilnius, capital of Lithuania, said that the joint
guarantees are basically possible, but all countries, including
the three Baltic states, have an inseparable right to independent
choice of its security and stability.
</P>
<P>
During the visit of British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook, who
arrived in Moscow last Sunday, NATO expansion, organized crime and
the situation in Bosnia were foremost topics for discussion
between the Russian and British foreign ministers.
</P>
<P>
Cook's visit was aimed at convincing that Russia will be "given
the opportunity" to contribute to European and world events. But
the two sides differed from each other over the arrest last week
of suspected war criminals in Bosnia by British forces.
</P>
<P>
When talking about the Russia-NATO ministerial meeting
scheduled for September in New York, Primakov suggested that the
issue of Bosnia be discussed and an armed force made of both
Russian and NATO troops be set up to deal with possible regional
conflicts.
</P>
<P>
Meeting with his visiting German counterpart, Klaus Kinkel, who
paid a short visit to Moscow Tuesday, Peimakov announced the
agenda for the Russia-NATO ministerial meeting scheduled in autumn
in New York, that is to address issues such as the Bosnian
situation, the peacekeeping mission, and international fight
against terrorism.
</P>
<P>
The two sides reached an agreement that Russia and Germany will
hold a regular summit since 1998 to further coordinate their
action and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Primakov repeatedly told Kinkel that NATO's eastward expansion
is the "biggest mistake" in Europe.
</P>
<P>
However, as part of the deal agreed upon, the alliance will
also stage a special conference in 1999 to review the broader
enlargement process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
