<DOCNO> XIE19970717.0057 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan's Reform Proposals on UN Budgeting System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Secretary-General Kofi
Annan announced today before the United Nations General Assembly
his recommendations for the reform of the UN budgeting system,
calling for a new one with solvency and development priorities.
</P>
<P>
In his recommendations reforming the budgeting system of the
United Nations, Annan proposes the following:
</P>
<P>
The Secretary-General proposes to the General Assembly a small
budget for the period of 1998-1999 as compared to the 1997-1998
period. This will be the first time in a generation there has been
negative growth, in real terms, in the United Nations budget.
</P>
<P>
The Secretary-General has initiated a series of measures to
reduce administrative costs to 25 percent of the budget as
compared to 38 percent currently. Savings are anticipated to grow
to at least 200 million dollars for the biennium beginning 2002.
</P>
<P>
Savings derived from three administrative efficiencies will be
utilized as a development dividend to fund the United Nations
highest priority such as the alleviation of poverty and the
generation of economic growth among developing countries.
</P>
<P>
The Secretary-General proposes creation of a revolving fund, to
be capitalized up to 1 billion dollars, as an interim solution to
the United Nations current fiscal crisis. This fund of voluntary
contributions by governments will give the United Nations
accessible operating capital at times when arrears in country dues
are causing significant cash-flow problems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
