<HEADLINE> Clinton Waives Controversial Part of Anti-Cuba Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 16 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
today decided to waive the controversial portions of an anti-Cuba
law for a third time since the law was enacted.
</P>
<P>
The Helms-Burton Act, designed to bring pressure on Cuba, was
signed into law in March last year. The law punishes foreign
firms trading with Cuba.
</P>
<P>
"The president again has decided to suspend the right to file
suit under Title Three for an additional six months,"
Undersecretary of State Stuart Eizenstat told a news conference.
</P>
<P>
Under sharp criticism from the world community, Clinton has
twice before waived the controversial Title Three of the law, in
July 1996 and January 1997. Under the title, any U.S. citizens
will have legal rights to sue foreign firms which use confiscated
property once owned by them.
</P>
<P>
The law, which was first proposed by Senator Jesse Helms and
Representative Dan Burton, has been bitterly criticized by Canada
and the European Union, arguing that it violates free trade
principles and international law.
</P>
<P>
Even Britain, which is the closest ally of the U.S., is also
strongly opposed to the law.
</P>
<P>
Eizenstat said that campaign against the Cuban government
would not be "strengthened by the institution of lawsuits."
"We must have the cooperation of our allies,"he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970717.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-16 19:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
