<HEADLINE> US Industrial Production Up 0.3 Percent in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 16 (Xinhua) -- The industrial production at
the U.S. factories, mines and utilities rose by a moderate 0.3
percent in June following a 0.2 percent gain in May, the U.S.
Federal Reserve (Fed) reported today.
</P>
<P>
The report said that the increase was mainly resulted from the
gain in the production of durable goods.
</P>
<P>
Paced by another sharp increase in the production of durable
consumer goods, the overall output of consumer goods rose 0.3
percent in the month with a 4 percent increase of vehicle. The
production of appliances and home computing equipment also posed
strong increase. The production of nondurable goods other than
energy products was flat and little changed from the previous
month.
</P>
<P>
For the second quarter as a whole, industrial production in the
U.S. grew at an annual rate of 4.3 percent, about the same rate as
in the previous two quarters.
</P>
<P>
The Fed report said that the output of construction supplies
fell by 0.4 percent in June and manufacturing output increased by
0.3 percent after identical increases in April and May.
</P>
<P>
In June, capacity utilization in the nation held steady at 83.5
percent. Economists believe an operating rate of 84 percent or
higher signals the development of inflationary bottlenecks in the
production pipeline. 
</P>
</TEXT>
