<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kagame Defends Congo on UN Investigation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Rwandan Vice-President and
Defense Minister Paul Kagame today defended Congolese President
Laurent Kabila's conditions for a U.N. investigation into alleged
massacres of Hutu refugees.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a news conference at the end of a one-day visit to
Kenya here, the Rwandan strong man said the investigation team
has to be neutral and that the probe had to be widened to cover a
longer period than that envisaged by the U.N.
</P>
<P>
He claimed that civilians in the eastern part of former Zaire
were routinely slaughtered by Rwandan Hutu refugees and
militiamen and this also warranted a U.N. investigation.
</P>
<P>
Kagame, whose National Patriotic Front rebels seized power in
Rwanda in 1994, admitted last week that Rwanda sent troops to
help Kabila topple President Mobutu Sese Seko in former Zaire,
now Democratic Congo, but Kabila said only Rwandan advisers had
been in his army.
</P>
<P>
"Kabila is demanding a wider scope of investigation into
killings in the Kivu region before and after he took power. I do
not see anything wrong in that," said Kagame.
</P>
<P>
Kagame said Kabila also wants neutral people to be members of
the probe and not just individuals who have formulated opinions
on the alleged killings.
</P>
<P>
U.N. chief Kofi Annan will soon name a new team to fly to
Kinshasa to probe the massacre reports after Kabila blocked an
inquiry led by Roberto Garreton of Chile.
</P>
<P>
Kagame came to Nairobi to mend fences with Kenya. He described
his talks with Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi as "cordial and
very fruitful", saying they have agreed to reopen the Rwandan
embassy in Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
The Rwandan embassy was shut down a year ago after a Rwandan
diplomat was implicated in an attempted assassination of an
exiled Rwandan Hutu politician in Nairobi. Kigali had then
accused Nairobi of helping Hutu dissidents who led, took part or
planned Rwanda's 1994 genocide of more than half a million
people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
