<HEADLINE> Greece's Central Bank Intervenes in Foreign </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, July 16 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of Greece today put a
large amount of funds in the country's foreign exchange market in
an effort to defend the Greek drachma, which came under pressure
from London banks.
</P>
<P>
The central bank reportedly sold 680 million ecu (about 2.19
million U.S. dollars) and 70 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The ecu parity was fixed at 309.92 drachmas, up 0.12 percent
from the previous day, while the U.S. dollar was slightly higher
at 281.50 drachmas.
</P>
<P>
The currency turmoil led to higher interest rates in the Greek
interbank market and also had a negative impact on the stock
market.
</P>
<P>
Investors were dumping drachmas in a rush to buy the U.S.
currency and sterling, which pushed up the two currencies on the
Greek market, The Bank of Greece sources said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
