<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-16 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Slams EU Membership Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Turkey today criticized a European
Commission's recommendation to start the European Union (EU)
membership talks with six countries but Turkey.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by Turkish Foreign Ministry said the
European Commission's decision to keep Turkey outside the
membership talks reflected "a discriminative and wrong approach."
</P>
<P>
"This approach contradicts with the EU commitment to equal and
objective standards applied to all candidate countries," the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
The European Commission agreed Tuesday to recommend six
nations, including Cyprus, Poland, the Czech Republic, Hungary,
Slovenia and Estonia, for a first wave of EU entry talks.
</P>
<P>
The exclusion of Turkey in the EU membership talks is
considered as an blow to Turkey's drive for full EU membership.
</P>
<P>
The statement also described the European Commission's
recommendation of Cyprus for the membership negotiations as "an
unjust choice."
</P>
<P>
In accordance with an agreement between the two countries in
1960, Cyprus could not participate in any international
organizations in which Turkey was not a member state.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus was divided into Turkish Cypriot North and Greek Cypriot
South When Turkish troops landed and took control of the northern
third of the island in 1974 following a coup seeking union with
Greece.
</P>
<P>
Turkish President Suleyman Demirel and Deputy Prime Minister
Bulent Ecevit also expressed their dissatisfaction with the
European Commission's recommendation while meeting with a senior
official from northern Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Demirel warned that the inclusion of Cyprus in the future EU
membership talks would bring a negative impact on the ongoing
Cyprus negotiations held between Cypriot President Glafcos
Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash in New York.
</P>
<P>
Ecevit threatened that Turkey and northern Cyprus would speed
up their integration process if the EU did not change its stance.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has been striving for a full EU membership in a bid to
give a big push to its economy, but failed to achieve this goal
due to a number of controversial issues with the EU.
</P>
<P>
European nations have cited Turkey's weak economy and human
rights record as hurdles for its pursuit of EU membership
application. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
