<HEADLINE> U.S. Refuses to Recognize Cambodia's New Co-premier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 16 (Xinhua) -- The United States said on
Wednesday that it would not recognize a replacement of First Prime
Minister Prince Norodom Ranariddh, which was reportedly decided by
a faction of his FUNCINPEC party this morning.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns told reporters the
United States was "very concerned" about the decision to make
Cambodian Foreign Minister Ung Huot Cambodia's co-prime minister
on Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
Ranariddh was overthrown by Second Prime Minister Hun Sen on
July 6 after Hun Sen moved his troops to make fierce attack on the
troops loyal to Prince Ranariddh and forced him into exile.
</P>
<P>
Hun Sen later said he wanted to keep the coalition between his
Cambodian People's Party and Ranariddh's FUNCINPEC in place and
required FUNCINPEC to choose a new first prime minister, hence
came the reported decision by the FUNCINPEC faction.
</P>
<P>
"We see no evidence whatsoever that FUNCINPEC has met... and
has elected on a free basis... a successor to Prince Ranariddh,"
Burns said at a briefing.
</P>
<P>
"We urge the authorities in Phnom Penh to refrain from
announcing a new first prime minister until Prince Ranariddh's
political party has an opportunity to make a reasoned decision on
this matter, free of coercion, free of intimidation," he
continued.
</P>
<P>
Burns said the United States had dealt "very cooperatively"
with Ung Huot as foreign minister in the past, "but we don't
recognize him as first prime minister, we recognize Prince
Ranariddh as first prime minister." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
