<HEADLINE> Mugabe Urges Development of National Languages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean President Robert Mugabe
today called for the development of indigenous languages, saying
this is vital of enhancing participatory democracy.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe, who was officially opening a three-day annual
conference and workshop of the Zimbabwe Languages Association
here, said indigenous languages should be used in all social,
political and economic pursuits.
</P>
<P>
He said, ''We as a nation must chart the way forward in order
to uplift the status, standard, and functional capacity of our
indigenous languages.''
</P>
<P>
''Failing to achieve this will bring the entire concept of
participatory democracy in Zimbabwe into question,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
He said the present and the future of indigenous languages
was, in fact, the present and future of local people.
</P>
<P>
Mugabe said, ''We cannot treat indigenous languages as if they
are dead or dying, relegating them to mere cadavers of linguistic
glory that once was.''
</P>
<P>
He noted that some people in Zimbabwe have tended, either
explicitly or implicitly, to despise indigenous languages in
which the country's culture is rooted.
</P>
<P>
The president appealed to the news media to take indigenous
languages seriously. ''Extensive use of our indigenous languages
will ensure that our people are better informed on all issues
that concern them and the nation as a whole,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
The event followed the language association's first annual
conference and workshop held in December last year, which
formulated a blueprint ''Mission Statement of the Zimbabwe
Languages Association on the Language Policy of Zimbabwe''.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
