<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Inland Area, Taiwan Scholars Discuss Source Of China's Rivers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scholars agreed here today
that the Yangtze and Yellow Rivers have nurtured people on both
sides of the Taiwan Straits.
</P>
<P>
"The Yangtze and Yellow River valleies were the common
birthplace of different ethnic groups in China," said Ru Xin,
vice-president of the Chinese Academy of Social Sciences, at a
meeting attended by more than 60 scholars from the inland areas,
Hong Kong and Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
The purpose of the "river culture" meeting was to give a boost
to the search for roots and to help strengthen national unity and
Chinese development in the next century, Ru explained.
</P>
<P>
The scholars will discuss the origins and evolution of the
Chinese nation by touching on a number of fields, like religion,
history, anthropology, and economics, and will visit important
sites along the Yellow River. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
