<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Negotiators Urged to Speed up Talks on Financial Services </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Chairman of Committee on Trade in
Financial Services in the World Trade Organization (WTO) Yoshio
Okubo has urged negotiators to continue to make efforts in order
to finish the talks by December 12, 1997 as scheduled, trade
sources said here today.
</P>
<P>
"Time is limited. Delegations should work hard," Okubo told
negotiators from WTO members, who began the negotiations on
financial services on April 10, 1997.
</P>
<P>
The negotiators hope to improve upon the package of
market-opening commitments agreed in July 1995, and to apply these
commitments equally, without discrimination, among all their
trading partners.
</P>
<P>
This would continue the process of progressive liberalization
that is one of the stated objectives of the General Agreement on
Trade in Services (GATS).
</P>
<P>
As of July 17, 1997, 26 members, including the 15 European
Union members, have submitted new offers. These members are
Australia, Bahrain, Canada, the EU members, Hong Kong, Hungary,
Japan, Norway, the Slovak Republic, Switzerland, Turkey, and the
United States, according to trade sources in Geneva. The offers
are conditional and subject to the overall outcome of the
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Since the package of market-opening commitments went into
effect on January 1, 1995, 96 members have made financial services
commitments in their Uruguay Round services schedules. As many as
43 of the 96 have improved their financial services commitments in
negotiations which ended on July 28, 1995.
</P>
<P>
Further meetings of the committee are planned for September,
October and November with a final meeting scheduled for December
12, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Brazil, the Czech Republic, Egypt, Israel, Macao, New Zealand,
Peru, Poland, Romania, and South Korea have said that they may
submit their offers by September. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
