<DOCNO> XIE19970717.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-17 15:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AL Slams U.S. Stance on Palestinian Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Saeed Kamal, Arab League Assistant
Secretary General for Palestinian Affairs, today denounced a U.S.
tendency to sidestep international resolutions on Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the Egyptian MENA news agency, he warned a
recent spate of academic studies in the U.S. "try to depict the
settling of Palestinians in other countries as the sole and
feasible option for solving the problem of Palestinian refugees."
</P>
<P>
He complained that the bulk of that research was intended to
skirt international resolutions in this regard.
</P>
<P>
"It is aimed at absolving Israel of any responsibility for the
issue and rephrasing the problem as merely one of rationing out
Palestinians between Israel and Arab countries," he said.
</P>
<P>
He warned that this would mean "depriving the Palestinians of
the right to return to their land."
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Washington voted against the UN General Assembly
resolution that condemns Israel's failure to stop the construction
of 6,500 homes for Jews in East Jerusalem, which the Palestinians
want as their future capital.
</P>
<P>
It had blocked two similar UN resolutions since Israel broke
ground for the Har Homa project, plunging the Mideast peacemaking
into four months of crisis.
</P>
<P>
On the current situation in the Mideast, Kamal charged that
Israel continues to place hurdles in front of the peace drive by
adopting a policy of "scuttling and ultimately destroying the
entire process," in defiance of Arab efforts to breathe life into
it.
</P>
<P>
"Israel's intensive settlement activity in East Jerusalem is
part of an ethnic cleansing campaign against the Palestinians that
strips off their identities and throws them out of Jerusalem to
manipulate the demographic structure of the holy city," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Arab League official said Israel's continued closure of
Palestinian lands and sapping of Palestinian economic resources,
specially water, have taken their heavy toll of Palestinian
economy that is already dilapidated by long years of occupation.
</P>
<P>
Kamal called for ensuring support for the Palestinian economy
especially by regional and international groups. 
</P>
</TEXT>
