<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia's Foreign Trade Slightly Down in First Five Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Russia's foreign trade fell 2.9
percent to 52.4 billion U.S. dollars in the first five months of
this year over the same period in 1995, the Interfax news agency
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Exports edged up 0.3 percent to 34.4 billion dollars, while
imports fell 8.5 percent to 18 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Interfax quoted the State Customs Committee as saying that
preliminary data showed the turnover of Russia's trade with
non-CIS countries and the CIS shrank by 0.2 percent and 10.9
percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
Trade with non-CIS countries accounted for 77 percent of
Russia's total foreign trade in the five months, a two percentage
point increase over the same period last year, while trade with
the CIS accounted for 22.9 percent, falling from 24.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
Russia's exports to non-CIS countries was virtually static at
27.3 billion dollars while exports to CIS countries rose 1.2
percent to 7.1 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said that energy exports' share of total exports rose
from 46 percent to 51 percent, while exports of ferrous and
nonferrous metals fell by 8.8 percent, although the nickel exports
grew by 25.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, imports from non-CIS countries accounted for 72.8
percent of total Russian imports between January and May 1997, up
from 67.2 percent in the same period in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Russia's imports from non-CIS countries fell marginally to 13
billion dollars, while those from the CIS stood fell 24 percent to
4.9 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Imports of machinery, equipment and vehicles totalled 5.9
billion dollars, accounting for 32.6 percent of total imports.
Four fifths of engineering imports came from non-CIS countries.
</P>
<P>
Other major import items were food and raw materials for food
processing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
