<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Qatar to Co-op with S.Africa, US on Liquefied Gas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Qatar has signed a memorandum of
understanding with companies from South Africa and the United
States on a liquefied natural gas project, the Qatari news agency
said today.
</P>
<P>
The project, with an investment of up to 500 million
U.S. dollars, is expected to be able to convert around 200 million
cubic feet of natural gas into 20,000 barrels of liquid fuels a
day.
</P>
<P>
The deal was signed in the Qatari capital Doha on Wednesday by
Qatar's Minister of Energy and Industry Abdullah Ben Hamad
al-Attiya, South Africa's synthetic fuel manufacturer Sasol Ltd
General Manager Pat Davies and Ted Sandridge, vice-president of
Global Ventures of the U.S. Phillips Petroleum.
</P>
<P>
The state-owned Qatar General Petroleum Corporation will hold
51 percent of the equity in the joint venture, while Sasol will
hold 34 percent, and Phillips Petroleum, the rest, according to
the new agency.
</P>
<P>
Qatar, one of the 11 members of the Organization of the
Petroleum Exporting Countries, has the world's third largest gas
reserves. 
</P>
</TEXT>
