<HEADLINE> Japanese Military Planes Return From Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Three Japanese military transport
planes returned home today after aborting their controversial
mission to fly to Cambodia to evacuate Japanese nationals.
</P>
<P>
The three C-130H transport aircraft from Japan's Air
Self-Defense Force (ASDF), which left the U-Taphao naval base 175
kilometers southeast of Bangkok earlier today, arrived back in
Japan's southernmost island prefecture of Okinawa, press reports
here said.
</P>
<P>
Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto decided Wednesday
night to withdraw the three ASDF transport planes from Thailand,
saying the violence in Cambodia had diminished and no longer
threatened Japanese nationals there.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto's decision to bring home the three ASDF planes came
six days after the prime minister dispatched the transport planes
to the U-Taphao naval base.
</P>
<P>
The planes and the ASDF had been waiting for orders since
Saturday for possible rescue operations to get Japanese nationals
out of Cambodia which was gripped by fighting between troops loyal
to Second Prime Minister Hun Sen who ousted his rival, First Prime
Minister Prince Norodom Ranariddh, last week.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto's decision to dispatch the military planes came under
criticism from some officials at the Foreign Ministry and the
Defense Agency.
</P>
<P>
"There is no law that provides a legal basis for sending the
planes to Thailand," one irritated Foreign Ministry official was
quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Takako Doi, leader of the Social Democratic Party (SDP) -- one
of two non-cabinet allies of the ruling Liberal Democratic Party
(LDP), also criticized the dispatch and said it had no legal
foundation.
</P>
<P>
To make things worse for Hashimoto, the Cambodian government
said Monday that it would not allow the Japanese planes to enter
Cambodia, noting that commercial airlines had resumed service.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
