<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Saddam Asks for Lifting of U.N. Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi President Saddam Hussein
here today asked the U.N. Security Council to lift the
seven-year-old sanctions imposed against Iraq since its invasion
of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
In a nationally-televised speech marking Iraq's 29th National
Day, Saddam said his country has "fulfilled its obligations under
the Security Council resolutions on eliminating weapons of mass
destruction."
</P>
<P>
"It is utterly unacceptable that the Security Council should
not acknowledge these sacrifices of Iraq and, in turn, fulfill its
obligations by lifting the embargo once and for all, completely
and comprehensively," he said.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has been seeking the lifting of the sanctions, which
forbid it selling oil and have inflicted devastating sufferings to
its people. However, the sanctions can only be lifted after a
U.N. special commission proves Iraq's full compliance in giving up
weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
The president attacked the U.S. for intending to prolong the
sanctions against his country in order to "continue to kill the
Iraqis by denying them food and medicine."
</P>
<P>
In an "oil-for-food" deal with the U.N., Iraq was allowed the
sale of 2 billion U.S. dollars worth of oil in a six-month period
for direly needed food and medicine. But it said its contracts
with foreign companies were repeatedly blocked by the U.S., thus
turning the deal into "oil-for-nothing."
</P>
<P>
Saddam said Iraq's relations with the U.N. Security Council
"will not stabilize unless the Security Council respects Iraq's
sovereignty and national security as it has stated and stressed in
its relevant resolutions."
</P>
<P>
He said "there is no way to stabilize the relations between the
U.N. Special Commission and its (Iraq's) concerns over its
national security and avoid provocations and manipulation."
</P>
<P>
The U.N. weapons inspection team has accused Baghdad of denying
its entry into delicate and sensitive sites and hiding weapons
that should have been scrapped.
</P>
<P>
As for the Palestine issue, Saddam appealed for Arab unity in
supporting the Palestinian cause and demanded Israel's
unconditional withdrawal from all occupied Arab territories.
</P>
<P>
The president condemned Turkish military operations in northern
Iraq aimed at wiping out Kurdish rebels and urged Ankara to
cooperate with neighboring states to ensure border security.
</P>
<P>
He deemed the military cooperation between Turkey and Israel as
a threat to the security of Iraq and the region as a whole.
</P>
<P>
In his speech, Saddam also criticized Iran's hostile policy
against Iraq. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
