<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada's CPI Up 1.8 Percent on Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Canadian consumers paid 1.8 percent
more than in June they did a year earlier for the goods and
services contained in the Consumer Price Index (CPI) basket,
Statistics Canada reported today.
</P>
<P>
The increase was primarily related to higher prices for such
big-budget items as new vehicles, vehicle insurance, clothing and
postsecondary tuition.
</P>
<P>
"However, Canadian consumers paid substantially less in
mortgage interest payments," the federal statistics agency said.
</P>
<P>
June's annual rate of CPI change was slightly higher than
April's (1.7 percent) and May's (1.5 percent), but lower than the
rates in the five preceding months (2.0 percent to 2.2 percent).
</P>
<P>
In monthly terms, the CPI rose by 0.2 percent in June. Higher
traveler accommodation rates had the most impact, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
Other price increases were noted for food, gasoline, air travel
and a number of personal-care products. Clothing and recreational
equipment prices declined, it added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
