<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Ends First Terrorism Trial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, July 17 (Xinhua) -- A Vietnamese court in Ho Chi Minh
City sentenced two men to death and three to life imprisonment
Tuesday in the country's first ever terrorism trial, the local
press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Huynh Te Cam, 39, and Tran Van Thuan, 29, were given the death
penalty for throwing grenades into a crowd at Bach Dang Wharf in
Ho Chi Minh City on October 13, 1994, which wounded 18 people,
including nine foreigners.
</P>
<P>
They were arrested on June 9, 1996 when they tried to enter
Vietnam at the Moc Bai border entry point with Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
Truong Van Duy, Pham Xuan Than and Nguyen Si Bang were
sentenced to life in prison for helping to organize the attack
which was designed to frighten foreign tourists and businessmen
and destabilize the country.
</P>
<P>
The five defendants belong to an exiled organization called the
"Resistance Front for the Restoration of Vietnam."
</P>
<P>
The organization has allegedly sent threatening letters to
foreigners telling them to stop investment and business in Vietnam
and leave the country as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
The organization also reportedly attempted to undermine the
eighth congress of the Communist Party of Vietnam which was held
in June last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
