<DOCNO> XIE19970717.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-17 14:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gulf Air Cuts Debts to 923 Million Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Gulf Air has sharply cut its
debts to 923 million U.S. dollars by the end of June from 1.566
billion dollars in December 1995, a statement issued by the
regional carrier said today.
</P>
<P>
A further reduction is anticipated before the end of 1997, the
statement said.
</P>
<P>
The Bahrain-based airline jointly owned by the governments of
Bahrain, Oman, Qatar and Abu Dhabi Emirate of the United Arab
Emirates (UAE) did not reveal its debts in 1996, but informed
sources said its debts amounted to an estimated 2 billion dollars
by the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
The debts, mostly in bank loans, resulted from a flurry of
buying new aircraft in the late 1980s and opening uneconomic
routes, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The debt-ridden carrier has cut jobs, sold aircraft and closed
unprofitable routes to cut losses.
</P>
<P>
At the end of 1996, the airline has sold six Boeing 767
aircraft and closed routes to and from New York, Geneva and
Johannesburg. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
