<DOCNO> XIE19970717.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Toy Tariff Hike Barely Affects HK Exports to Brazil </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Brazil's safeguard measures on
toys show little impact on Hong Kong's total exports to the South
American country, said the Hong Kong Trade Development Council
(TDC) today.
</P>
<P>
A TDC report said Brazil's stable economy will stimulate import
demand for other products. This should more than offset the
negative impact of the tariff hike.
</P>
<P>
From January 1, 1997 to December 1999, Brazil will impose
additional duties on some categories of imported toys, and the
revised total tariff rate will be 63 percent in 1997, 49 percent
in 1998 and 35 percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
Although the safeguard measures will seriously hamper Hong
Kong's toy exports to Brazil, they only slightly affect Hong
Kong's overall exports to Brazil, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Figures showed that affected toys account for less than one
percent of Hong Kong's overall domestic exports to Brazil and 9.2
percent of its re-exports.
</P>
<P>
Over the past few years, Hong Kong exports to Brazil have grown
rapidly. Total exports to Brazil more than tripled between 1993
and 1995. Following a five percent drop in 1996, Hong Kong exports
to Brazil recorded an increase of 33 percent during the first four
months of this year, reaching 2.85 billion HK dollars (365.38
Million U.S. dollars). 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
