<HEADLINE> Probe Mounted Into Spying Allegation Against </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 17 (Xinhua) -- The Turkish military has launched a
probe to find out if former deputy Prime Minister Tansu Ciller
works for the U.S. Central Intelligence Agency (CIA), all the
local newspapers reported today.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Chief of General Staff Ismail Hakki Karaday has given
an order to the military public prosecutor's office to make such
an investigation against Ciller, who is also leader of the True
Path Party, the newspapers said.
</P>
<P>
If found guilty of espionage, Ciller would face a trial in the
supreme court, said the reports.
</P>
<P>
The spying allegations against Ciller were first made in late
June by Worker's Party Chairman Dogu Perincek who claimed Ciller
has been working for the CIA since 1967.
</P>
<P>
Perincek accused Ciller, also former foreign minister, in a
petition to the prosecutor of "accepting money and benefits from
foreigners with the intention of acting against the national
interests".
</P>
<P>
Perincek also said that Ciller received training by the CIA
and that she had been active on behalf of the CIA in the former
Soviet Union and in Libya. 
</P>
</TEXT>
