<HEADLINE> Chinese FM Spokesman On Korean Peninsula Situation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Foreign Ministry Spokesman Tang
Guoqiang said today that China does not want to see any tension on
the Korean peninsula and believes that a worsening of the
situation there is not in the interest of the parties concerned.
</P>
<P>
When asked at a press conference here this afternoon about
China's view on the armed conflict on the peninsula yesterday,
Tang said that China hopes the parties concerned will consider the
overall situation of safeguarding peace and stability on the
peninsula and deal with the event in a sober way.
</P>
<P>
In commenting on the coming talks among the Democratic People's
Republic of Korea, the Republic of Korea, the United States and
China, Tang said that China welcomes the talks and believes that
the establishment of a peace mechanism on the Korean Peninsula
will serve long-term stability and peace there and help improve
relations between the parties involved.
</P>
<P>
China hopes that those parties will take part in the talks in a
sincere and frank way, Tang noted.
</P>
<P>
China has already announced that it will take part in the
four-party talks and will play a constructive role in setting up
the peace mechanism on the Korean Peninsula, the spokesman
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
