<DOCNO> XIE19970717.0108 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Chemical Fertilizer Plant For Northwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Northwest China's Gansu Province
will have a greater supply of chemical fertilizer when a new
chemical fertilizer plant goes operational at the Lanzhou Chemical
Industry Corp. (LCIC) in August.
</P>
<P>
The plant will use residual oil to produce 300,000 tons of
synthetic ammonia and 520,000 tons of carbamide annually for grain
production, according to Zhu Lianbao, general manager of the
company.
</P>
<P>
Chemical fertilizers play a vital role in increasing Gansu's
grain output, but because of short supplies, the average amount of
chemical fertilizers applied in Gansu is about 75 percent lower
than the national average.
</P>
<P>
"The shortage of chemical fertilizer has become a drag on the
province's agricultural production," Governor Sun Ying explains.
</P>
<P>
The new plant is actually an expansion project at an old LCIC
plant. Gansu and the Chinese Petrochemical Corp (Sinopec) have
spent more than 2.8 billion yuan (337 million US dollars) on the
project.
</P>
<P>
"We imported advanced equipment and technology from Germany,
the U.S., and Italy in order to enhance automation and to reduce
the consumption of energy and the discharge of industrial waste,"
Zhu said, pointing out that expanding production capacity of an
old factory in this way is more economical than building a new one.
</P>
<P>
The success of the chemical fertilizer project will be an
example of renovation in this west China's petrochemical giant
with its 45 major plants producing more than 110 kinds of
products, such as chemical fertilizers, synthetic rubbers,
synthetic fibers and petroleum products.
</P>
<P>
"After decades of operation, the company needs an overall
technological renovation to improve production conditions and
increase economic efficiency," he noted.
</P>
<P>
The company is planning to expand its ethylene production
capacity to satisfy the growing demand for agriculture-related
materials in northwest and southwest China, including plastic
sheeting and plastic pipe for irrigation.
</P>
<P>
"New ethylene projects will not only help us expand the
business, but also spur the local economic growth since related
industries will be developed," Zhu said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
