<HEADLINE> Kenyan Senior Official Praises China News Agency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Kenya is very happy to see that
China's news reporting on the eastern African country "is
balanced and have no bias," said Kenyan Minister for Information
and Broadcasting Johnstone Makau today.
</P>
<P>
This forms a sharp contrast with western media which paints a
"very negative picture" of Kenya and a lot of other African
countries, he said, adding that such a picture damaged the image
of the continent and reduced the foreign arrivals.
</P>
<P>
Xinhua News Agency, China's official new agency which has set
a branch here for more than 20 years, covers news in balance for
Kenya and other developing nations with "no wrong pictures
given," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan minister spoke highly of the long-term sound
cooperation between Xinhua and the Kenyan News Agency (KNA) at a
ceremony at which the Xinhua donated equipment worth some 1.5
million Shillings (28,000 U.S. Dollars) was handed over to KNA.
</P>
<P>
The donation to KNA, Kenya's national news service founded in
1963, included computers, printers, cameras, facsimile machines
and other telecommunication equipment.
</P>
<P>
A big scheme has been underway to modernize KNA with
up-to-date information technology, he said, expressing the hope
that China can help more as KNA-Xinhua cooperation deepens during
KNA's modernization process.
</P>
<P>
He said that China has continuously offered technical
assistance to Kenya in social, cultural and other fields over
recent years.
</P>
<P>
"The bilateral relations existing between Kenya and China are
very very cordial and very warm," he added.
</P>
<P>
In response, Chinese Ambassador An Yongyu said China attaches
importance to its relations with Kenya and is satisfied with the
recent smooth and fruitful development of ties through the
exchanges of visits by top leaders of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
"We are helping each other sincerely and we hope we can do
more," An said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
