<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Liberal Democratic Party Leader on Sino-Japanese Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 17 (Xinhua) -- The secretary-general of Japan's
Liberal Democratic Party (LDP), Kato Koichi, told the Chinese
Press here today that Japan and China should strengthen dialogue,
establish relations of mutual trust, and joint efforts to enter a
new century of peace and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Kato, who is in Beijing as guest of the Communist Party of
China (CPC), said that one of the purposes of his visit is to
discuss bilateral relations and a wide range of international
issues with Chinese leaders, and to carry a message on Japan's
determination for peaceful development and Sino-Japanese
friendship.
</P>
<P>
This visit has been fruitful in that co-operative relations
between the ruling parties of the two countries have been
reaffirmed, he explained.
</P>
<P>
Japan and China normalized diplomatic relations 25 years ago
and bilateral ties have grown smoothly on the whole, he noted. In
the past decade or so, economic and trade co-operation has become
better, but political contacts have not had enough emphasis,
something that has resulted in some problems.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, it is time for the two countries to make a decision
to expand co-operation, especially between young politicians, he
noted.
</P>
<P>
He pointed to Japan's spirit of deep introspection for the
untold suffering it caused the people of Asia, something that was
explained by former Prime Minister Tomiichi Murayama in his speech
two years ago.
</P>
<P>
Some people in Japan are calling for a re-definition of
historical issues, but they are in the minority, Kato said,
expressing his hope that both sides will reach an agreement on
this point through discussions and consultations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
