<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Officials Told to Use Cars Within State Standards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 17 (Xinhua) -- China's Central Commission for
Discipline Inspection and the Ministry of Supervision have issued
a circular urging officials to stop using cars that are better
than called for in their work.
</P>
<P>
The circular comes at a time when the Guangdong Provincial
Commission for Discipline Inspection and the province's Supervision
Department are dealing with three cases involving local officials
buying cars that exceeded standards set by the central government.
</P>
<P>
In early 1994, officials with the provincial Education
Commission there bought two Crown Toyota cars with 826,000 yuan
(99,500 US dollars), 796,000 yuan of which had been intended for
educational funds.
</P>
<P>
Six officials, including Xu Renzhi, director of the Education
Commission, were given Party disciplinary warnings, and the two
cars were confiscated and auctioned.
</P>
<P>
Zhou Xuchuan and Yang Chunyi, general manager and deputy
general manager respectively of the Agricultural Machinery
Corporation in Heping County of Heyuan City, Guangdong, were
removed from their posts and given Party discipline for buying a
Volkswagen Santana and two mobile phones with 244,000 yuan in
poverty-relief loans in January.
</P>
<P>
The third case involves Liao Bin, vice-mayor of Qingyuan
County, and is still under investigation. Liao used a Crown Toyota
that exceeded state standards from January to March of this year.
</P>
<P>
The circular points out that the Communist Party of China
Central Committee and the State Council have worked out a
series of decrees on the use of cars by officials, but some
officials have ignored these regulations.
</P>
<P>
It calls on officials to learn from these cases under review,
and they are reminded that those found violating the decrees will
be severely penalized. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
