<HEADLINE> East China Coastal City to Develop Five Pillar Industries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, July 17 (Xinhua) -- The coastal city of Fuzhou, capital
of east China's Fujian Province, will focus on five pillar
industries to increase its industrial output value by 37.5 billion
yuan by the end of the century.
</P>
<P>
These industries include electronics and machinery, light
industry and textiles, the chemical industry, aquatics, and
building materials.
</P>
<P>
They are expected to produce a total of 143.3 billion yuan in
output value in 2000, which will account for 48.7 percent of the
GNP.
</P>
<P>
The city plans to spend more than 13 billion yuan on 41 key
projects in electronics and machinery, with an average annual
increase of nearly 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
For light industry and textiles, Fuzhou will invest 10 billion
yuan on 67 key projects, aiming at an annual growth of 25.2
percent.
</P>
<P>
Some 3.2 billion yuan will go to 21 major projects in the
chemical industry, to attain an average increase of 19.6 percent
in output value.
</P>
<P>
The city is to yield 1.25 million tons of aquatic products by
the end of the century. And building materials will contribute 30
billion yuan in annual output value to rank second after
electronics and machinery among the five industries.  
</P>
</TEXT>
