<HEADLINE> Cameroun National Assembly Session Okeys Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, July 17 (Xinhua) -- The first ordinary session of the
National Assembly of Cameroun for the 1997/1998 legislative year
came to a close in Yaounde last night after parliamentarians
adopted a total of five bills presented by the Camerounian
government.
</P>
<P>
Prior to the closing ceremony, the state budget for the
1997/1998 fiscal year which stands at 1256 billion CFA francs was
adopted by the house.
</P>
<P>
The budget which has been forwarded to the head of state for
promulgation into law was drawn up to stimulate economic recovery
and sustainable development.
</P>
<P>
The budget shows an increase of 13 percent on the 1996/1997
estimate.
</P>
<P>
Opened on June 17, the first ordinary session had validated
171 out of 173 newly elected parliamentarians. A 23-member
executive bureau of the national assembly was elected. Cavaye
Djibril won another mandate as the speaker of the house. The six
committees of the national assembly were inaugurated.
</P>
<P>
Major differences can be seen from this session to that of the
last year. The main difference has been at the level of the
political configuration of the house.
</P>
<P>
For the last assembly, there were four political parties,
namely the Cameroun People's Democratic Movement (CPDM), the
National Union for Democracy and Progress (NUDP), the Union for
the People of Cameroun (UPC) and the Movement for Democracy and
the Republic (MDR).
</P>
<P>
With this new assembly, three parties added to the four
parties of the last assembly. They are: the Social Democratic
Front (SDF), the Union for Democracy and Change (UDC) and the
Mouvement Pour La Jeunesse du Dameroun (MLJC) (Movement for the
Youth of Cameroun). 
</P>
</TEXT>
