<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australian Workers in Arts Poorly Paid: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Half a million Australians, or 7
percent of the country's work force, earn some income from
arts-related work although most professionals are poorly paid
despite high qualifications, said a report released here today.
</P>
<P>
Margaret Seares, who was newly appointed chairwoman of the
Australia Council, said Artswork, a report on Australians working
in the arts, showed the days were gone when arts was correctly
described as a fringe area.
</P>
<P>
"Sadly, artists remain among the most poorly paid professionals
in the country despite a level of education nearly double the
national average," she said.
</P>
<P>
Of the most recent figures available (1992-1993), the average
income for artists remains at only about 15,000 U.S. dollars and
in some arts professions such as dance the average income is as
low as 9,000 U.S. dollars, Seares said.
</P>
<P>
By comparison, the average income for the whole work force is
24,300 U.S. dollars in para-professional occupations, and 28,100
U.S. dollars in managerial occupations.
</P>
<P>
The report, the result of research by the Australian Bureau of
Statistics and work by Australia's leading arts researcher David
Throsby, covers work in a diverse range of cultural and leisure
activities, including museums, art galleries and libraries to
radio, television, film, design, photography, jewelry, writing,
publishing, visual arts and performing arts as well as people who
were ticket sellers, ushers or stage hands.
</P>
<P>
Of the half million Australians earning some income from arts
work, the biggest group are in writing or publishing (133,000),
followed by arts teaching (120,000) and music performance
(67,000).
</P>
<P>
"There are about 40,000 practicing professional artists working
full time or part time in an expanding arts sector," Seares said.
</P>
<P>
The arts work force increased by a phenomenal 23 percent in the
late 1980s, when the total work force grew just 9 percent.
</P>
<P>
The report says most arts workers live and work in the major
capital cities, while Sydney has 32 percent of all the workers.
</P>
<P>
The average age of practicing professional artists is 44,
compared with the work force average of 37, with writers tending
to be older (on average 54), visual artists (44), and dancers the
youngest group at 26.
</P>
<P>
About 60 percent of people whose main job is in the arts are
men, but the breakup of the sexes is very different in particular
areas.
</P>
<P>
Eighty percent of Australia's announcers are men, 74 percent of
the musicians are men, while 51 percent of authors are women, as
are 67 percent of dancers and choreographers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970717.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
