<HEADLINE> Indian PM Cancels Visit to Malaysia, Singapore </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 17 (Xinhua)-- Indian Prime Minister Inder Kumar
Gujral has canceled his proposed visit to Malaysia and Singapore
beginning on July 26, the local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Gujral, in his capacity as minister of external affairs, was
scheduled to visit Kuala Lumpur to attend the foreign ministerial
meeting of the Asean Regional Forum (ARF) and stop over in
Singapore for two days on his way home.
</P>
<P>
Official sources here said that the prime minister canceled his
trip because the vice-presidential election would be held on
August 16.
</P>
<P>
But some observers here believed that the reason behind the
decision was that the prime minister had to first put in order his
crisis-ridden United Front.
</P>
<P>
Following the split of the Janata Dal, the largest constituent
of the ruling United Front, earlier this month, another major
constituent, the Dravida Munnetra Kazhagam (DMK), on Monday
threatened to withdraw from the 13-party front.
</P>
<P>
The DMK in a statement accused some United Front leaders of
pursuing personal agenda at the cost of the unity of the front.
This referred to the insistence by former prime minister H.D. Deve
Gowda and the left parties that the breakaway wing of the Janata
Dal, led by Bihar Chief Minister Laloo Prasad Yadav, be kept out
of the ruling front.
</P>
<P>
Laloo Prasad Yadav, who was former Janata Dal president and a
rival of former prime minister Gowda, has been charged in a
scandal in which huge sums of public funds for purchasing fodder
have been embezzled in Bihar.
</P>
<P>
Gowda and the left parties, among others, have been pressing
Yadav to resign from the post of Bihar chief minister, resulting
in the split of the Janata Dal.
</P>
<P>
Yadav, who floated the Rashtriya Janata Party in defiance of
pressure for him to quit, has voiced support to the Gujral
government and wanted to stay in the United Front.
</P>
<P>
The DMK will take a final decision on its withdrawal on July 27
unless the parties concerned within the United Front can iron out
their differences before that date.
</P>
<P>
On behalf of Gujral, Finance Minister P. Chidambaram and
Minister of State for External Affairs Salim Shervani will attend
the ARF foreign ministers' meeting.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
