<DOCNO> XIE19970717.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Saudi Aramco Signs Deal on Joint Venture with US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, July 17 (Xinhua) -- A state-owned Saudi oil
company has signed a memorandum of understanding with two
U.S. oil companies to form a new three-partner joint venture to
market gasoline and other refined oil products.
</P>
<P>
This was announced Wednesday night by the Saudi Arabian Oil
Company (Saudi Aramco) in the Saudi city of Dhahranin in a press
release, which was reported by the Saudi Press Agency.
</P>
<P>
The new venture of Aramco and Shell as well as Texaco
Incorporation would sell products under both the Texaco and Shell
brands through existing outlets.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi Aramco is the world's largest oil-producing company,
with integrated operations in exploration, production, refining
and marketing.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi Aramco's initial ownership interest in the new joint
venture, Eastern Region Company, will be 32.5 percent, with 32.5
percent held by Texaco and 35 percent by Shell, the release
said.
</P>
<P>
The chief executives of the three companies said in a joint
statement that "we believe this combination of the three
companies' assets will allow us to accomplish fundamental
changes in the way we operate our downstream businesses, leading
to improved customer service, performance and growth."
</P>
<P>
Currently, Texaco-branded products are sold by Star Enterprise,
a 50 to 50 joint venture between subsidiaries of Texaco and Saudi
Aramco.
</P>
<P>
The three companies expect the new organization to result in
greater profitability and productivity through the sharing of
management systems, business processes and other efficiencies, the
release said.
</P>
<P>
The new alliance will combine the refining strength of Star
Enterprise with the strong U.S. eastern region marketing
presence of Shell.
</P>
<P>
The Saudi Aramco will continue to supply the majority of
approximately 600,000 barrels of oil per day processed by Star's
three U.S.-based refineries.
</P>
<P>
The consolidation of Shell and Star assets will create one of
the largest refining and marketing networks in the United States.
</P>
<P>
Pending completion of regulatory reviews and definitive
agreements, all Texaco, Star Enterprise and Shell downstream
facilities will continue to operate separately.
</P>
<P>
The exploration, production and chemical businesses of the
companies are not part of the new joint venture, the release
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970717.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
