<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cease-fire Monitors Warn Stepped-up Violence in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, July 17 (Xinhua) -- An international panel warned
today that a cease-fire agreement implemented in south Lebanon
since last year was in peril due to intensified fightings between
Israeli forces and Lebanese Hezbollah guerrilla.
</P>
<P>
The five-nation cease-fire monitoring committee blamed Lebanon
and Israel equally for the "quickening chain of action and
reaction that is likely to shake" the cease-fire understanding
reached between the two countries in April, 1996.
</P>
<P>
"Responsible authorities are called upon to exercise caution
and self-restraint in order to defuse tensions and protect
civilians living on both sides of the border," said the committee
in a communique released at the end of its meeting today.
</P>
<P>
The cease-fire monitoring committee, grouping France, Israel,
Lebanon, Syria and the United States, held Israel responsible for
the deaths of three civilians killed "deliberately or
unintentionally" in shellings on south Lebanese villages earlier
this week.
</P>
<P>
It said Lebanon was also to blame for the resurgent barrages
of Katyusha rockets fired on the border of Israel's Galilee
panhandle in the past two days although no casualties or damages
on the Israeli side were reported from the missile assaults.
</P>
<P>
A member of the Lebanese delegation to the committee who
declined to be named said that his team explained to the plenary
meeting the Katyusha barrages were fired on northern Israel in
retaliation for Israeli attacks that caused civilian casualties.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese delegation said the civilian population of the
country should be protected on equal level with Israel's northern
settlers under the 1996 April understanding, which was mediated
by former U.S. Secretary of State Warren Christopher to halt a
17-day Israeli blitz in south Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
"Combatants are responsible for the methods with which they
perform their combat missions and should be aware of the
consequences of their action," the committee communique said.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Lebanese House Speaker Nabih Berri
urged the monitoring committee to "undertake more vigor in
preventing Israeli aggression."
</P>
<P>
Berri accused the Jewish state of "deliberately escalating
hostilities every summer to jolt the progress of Lebanon's
recovery" from the disasters of the 1975-90 civil war.
</P>
<P>
Yet Berri, who heads the pro-Syrian Amal militia that rivals
Hezbollah for supremacy in Lebanon's Shiite Muslim community,
ruled out a repetition of Israel's "Grapes of Wrath" operation,
saying "I don't expect a large-scale Israeli attack in the near
future." 
</P>
</TEXT>
