<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ECOWAS, Sierra Leone to Talk Over Crisis </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, July 17 (Xinhua) -- The Economic Community of West
African States (ECOWAS) and the Sierra Leonean military
government led by Major Johnny Koromah are to hold talks in
Abidjan, Cote d'Ivoire today.
</P>
<P>
The one-day talk is expected to find an acceptable solution to
the crisis caused by the military government's taking power by
force from elected president Ahmed Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
The ECOWAS team to the talks is led by Nigerian Foreign
Minister Tom Ikimi, with the participation of the his
counterparts from Ghana, Guinea and Cote d'Ivoire.
</P>
<P>
ECOWAS has in more than one cases made clear its standing that
coup is no more acceptable in today's world and that the
legitimate government of President Kabbah must be restored.
</P>
<P>
ECOWAS is more determined today than at any time to ensure the
peace and stability of the west African sub-region not be
disturbed, as its efforts to bring peace in Liberia is near to
the final success, with the presidential and legislative
elections to be held in that country just Saturday.
</P>
<P>
However, having consolidated its power in nearly two months,
with the swearing-in of Major Koromah himself as the head of
state and the appointment of a 17-man cabinet, the new military
government is less likely to give in.
</P>
<P>
Leaving for the Abidjan talks Wednesday at the Freetown
airport held by ECOWAS soldiers, the new Sierra Leonean Chief
Secretary of State Solomon Musa said, "We are going to put the
case for the coup across at last."
</P>
<P>
He lamented that the international community has not given the
new government the opportunity to explain itself but had
condemned it outright.
</P>
<P>
Major Koromah has repeatedly said that he had come to power to
correct the bad situation in Sierra Leone during Kabbah's rule,
by which he means that Kabbah has failed to make peace with the
rebel forces of Foday Sanko, the Revolutionary United Front.
</P>
<P>
Koromah has done this and that is a great strength of him.
</P>
<P>
Thus as he promised to go back to barracks once peace is in
the country, Koromah also warned, "Now that peace is at our
doorstep. If we allow it to slip away, we shall never get it
again because the rebels will not go back to the bush."
</P>
<P>
Koromah is not, of course, looking for a head-on collision
with ECOWAS, and indeed, the international society.
</P>
<P>
According to a foreign ministry official in Freetown, the
military government will press for the formation of a broad-based
government at the Abidjan talks.
</P>
<P>
The new thing with such a broad-based government is that it
will include toppled former president Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
Before this, Koromah has refused to let Kabbah back and
actually said that Kabbah can only return to Freetown to face
imprisonment for inviting foreign intervention. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
