<HEADLINE> High Agricultural Growth Neutralizes Economic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 17 (Xinhua)-- A phenomenal growth of 5.7
percent in India's agriculture, forestry and fishing sector has
made up for a slowdown in the country's manufacturing sector and
enabled the economy to grow 6.8 percent in the fiscal year 1996-97
(April 1996-March 1997), according to Central Statistical
Organization (CSO) sources here today.
</P>
<P>
The CSO had earlier estimated that output in the manufacturing
sector would grow 10.6 percent in 1996-97 over the previous year.
The revised estimates now indicate that the manufacturing sector
might have grown 8.1 percent in 1996-97.
</P>
<P>
The revised estimates show that the manufacturing sector slowed
down substantially in 1996-97. It had grown 13.6 percent in
1995-96.
</P>
<P>
Growth in trade, hotels, transport and communication slowed
down from 13.3 percent in 1995-96 to 8.7 percent in 1996-97.
</P>
<P>
The value of output in community, social and personal services
increased 5.3 percent in 1996-97, down from 6.2 percent in
1995-96.
</P>
<P>
The CSO releases estimates of gross domestic product every
quarter. Its estimate of an overall economic growth of 6.8 percent
in 1996-97, made in January, has been retained in the revised
estimate due to big 5.7 percent increase in agriculture. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
