<DOCNO> XIE19970717.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kazakh Airlines Crew Responsible for Mid-air </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 17 (Xinhua) -- The Kazakh IL-76 aircraft flight
crew has been held responsible by an Indian court of inquiry for
the mid-air collision between it and a Saudia Jumbo near New
Delhi, capital of India, on November 12 last year, killing all the
349 people on board, the local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The black boxes of the two aircraft, which gave vital clues to
the probable cause of the collision, were decoded at the Air
Accident Investigation Branch under the Department of Transport in
the UK, and at Inter-State Aviation Committee, Moscow,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
The reports of the two institutions have clearly established
that the incoming Kazakh aircraft was not at its assigned level of
15,000 feet and came down to the flight level of approximately
14,000 feet, resulting in the mid-air collision.
</P>
<P>
Justice R.C. Lahoti, who headed the court inquiry, has said
that it was up to the government to accept the findings and the
recommendations of the court of inquiry.
</P>
<P>
A 200-page report of the court of inquiry has been submitted to
Civil Aviation Minister C.M. Ibrahim.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
