<HEADLINE> Arthur Andersen Taps Potential in China Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 17 (Xinhua) -- A representative for Arthur
Andersen, a world giant in the accounting business, said today
that the company will further expand its operations in China in
the coming years.
</P>
<P>
The economic reform and development in China has provided great
opportunities in investment and trade to the world and "there is
almost no limit to the opportunities for the accounting profession
in China," John Burrows, Arthur Andersen's area managing partner
of the Asia-Pacific region, said at a press conference here today.
</P>
<P>
Burrows said that his colleagues are all "keenly aware" of the
impact that developments in China can have on other economies in
the Asia-Pacific region.
</P>
<P>
"As China's financial infrastructure grows, and as its
businesses become more sophisticated and complex, and compete in
the global marketplace, the demands for our accounting, tax and
consulting services will increase dramatically," he said.
</P>
<P>
Arthur Andersen started its business in China in 1979, and in
1983 became the first foreign accounting firm to establish a
representative office in China.
</P>
<P>
To date, Arthur Andersen has assisted some 39 Chinese firms
with their listings of stocks and issuance of bonds in Hong Kong,
New York and London, valued at a total of five billion
U.S. dollars. It has also provided accounting and consulting
services to more than 50 power plants in China.
</P>
<P>
Burrows forecast that Arthur Andersen's revenue from its China
business will reach 100 million U.S. dollars this year, up 34
percent from last year. The growth rate is compared to a predicted
12 percent increase in the overall revenue from its global
business.
</P>
<P>
Arthur Andersen plans to double it present scale of business in
China by the end of the century, Burrows said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
