<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Seeks Normalization of Ties with Kuwait </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian Prime Minister
Abdul-Salam Majali has expressed hope that his country will
restore fully the strained ties with Kuwait, stressing that
Jordan was now fully open to the Gulf state.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Kuwait's Arabic daily Al-Rai Al-Aam, which
was published today, the Jordanian prime minister said that
"clouds that have prevailed above the Arab world have just passed
peacefully" and "for our part, we are fully open to Kuwait."
</P>
<P>
He said disputes between his country and Kuwait were a "family
difference" and "occasional," referring to the time when Jordan
was accused of siding with Iraq which occupied its neighbor of
Kuwait during the 1990-1991 Gulf crisis.
</P>
<P>
Majali hailed the restoration of flights between Kuwait City
and Amman and other positive developments including Kuwaiti
investments in Jordan.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait and Jordan resumed direct airlinks starting from July
9, heralding a full-scale normalization of relations between
the two Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait has been inching toward renewing its ties with Jordan
that were frozen after the government accused Amman of supporting
Iraq before and after the 1991 Gulf War to end the Iraqi invasion
of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian Foreign Minister Fayez Tarawneh held talks with
Kuwaiti acting Prime Minister and Foreign Minister Sheikh Sabah
Al-Ahmad Al-Jaber Al-Sabah in late June to discuss the issues
related to speeding up the normalization of relations between the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
Their discussions included an expected visit by the Kuwaiti
foreign minister himself to Jordan.
</P>
<P>
However, Tarawneh ruled out the possibility of ties-breaking
with Iraq for the sake of mending fences with Kuwait, pointing
out that "we are friends of the Gulf (states) and Iraq."
</P>
<P>
"In our relations with Kuwait, we reject the principle of
whether it should be completely white or black," he said.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait has a charge d'affaires in Amman, but there is no
Jordanian mission in Kuwait now.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian prime minister did not say whether there is a
timetable for his country to re-open the embassy in Kuwait which
has so far remained closed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970717.0144 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Trade Pressure Mounts on India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, July 17 (Xinhua) -- With the United States and
Australia requesting the World Trade Organization (WTO) for
dispute settlement consultations, pressure has mounted on India to
come to terms with its major trading partners on the question of
withdrawal of quantitative restrictions on imports within the next
couple of months, Commerce Ministry sources said here today.
</P>
<P>
Following the failure of the June 30-July 1 talks between India
and its western trading partners, it was expected that some of
them might move the WTO dispute settlement mechanism. Their
decision to do so has provided another opportunity for India to
present its case for a sufficiently longer period for phasing out
import restrictions and arrive at a mutually acceptable program,
they said.
</P>
<P>
India claimed that it had shown flexibility in offering to
phase out restrictions in six years, but that was rejected by the
US and other western countries. The latter wanted India to ease
its import restrictions within the next 2-3 years.
</P>
<P>
In the three rounds of talks with its trade partners under the
aegis of the WTO Balance of Payment Committee since 1995, India
had been able to delay notifying a program of phasing out import
licensing and quota. But, according to international trade
analysts, it is no longer possible to indefinitely delay the
removal of import restrictions since the US and Australian move
has now triggered off the time-bound WTO dispute settlement
procedure.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
