<DOCNO> XIE19970717.0148 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-17 09:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Family Planning Brings Down Birth Rate in Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 17 (Xinhua) -- The national birth rate in Egypt
witnessed a noticeable decline in the last decade thanks to the
family planning program.
</P>
<P>
Lastest census figures released by the Central Agency for
Mobilization and Statistics (CAMS) show that the national birth
rate has declined to 2.1 percent in 1996 from 2.8 percent in 1986.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's total population was stabilized at 61 million last
year, 4 million less than expected, according to CAMS Chairman
Ihab Elwi.
</P>
<P>
The average family size has also shrunk to 4.6 members from 4.9.
</P>
<P>
The number of women using contraceptives has more than doubled
over the last 15 years. In 1980 only 24 percent of women of
child-bearing age used contraceptives compared to 49 percent in
1995.
</P>
<P>
The birth rate decline is despite an expanded productive age
group during the past 10 years. Those aged between 15 and 60
accounted for 59.9 percent of the population last year, higher
than the 53.8 percent in 1986, said Elwi.
</P>
<P>
Egypt's family planning program focused on ensuring the
availability of contraceptives, provision of family planning
services and centers, better reproductive health and prenatal
care, as well as enhancing public awareness.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the tendency to marry late also contributed
to the decline in the population growth rate, said Elwi.
</P>
<P>
The number of married decreased to 61.2 percent of the
population in 1996 from 64.8 percent in 1986, while the unmarried,
excluding the widows and widowers, accounted for 27.8 percent of
the population, compared to 25.7 percent a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the census revealed that the illiteracy rate among
the Egyptians has declined from 49.6 percent to 38.6 percent, with
university degree-holders representing 7.3 percent of the
population, compared to 4.3 percent ten years ago.
</P>
<P>
The workforce rose to 35.4 percent of the population last year
from 34.4 percent in 1986. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
