<HEADLINE> Pakistan to Continue Peace Efforts in Afghanistan: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan will continue its
diplomatic efforts to bring the Afghan warring factions to the
negotiating table, a Foreign Office spokesman said here today.
</P>
<P>
In the past two weeks, the Pakistani delegation led by
Additional Foreign Secretary Iftikhar Murshed has held extensive
talks respectively with the leadership of the Islamic Taliban
militia and anti-Taliban northern alliance, the spokesman told a
weekly news briefing here.
</P>
<P>
During the meetings, the two sides exchanged views regarding
steps that would lead the two sides to the negotiating table, he
said.
</P>
<P>
"Because of their (the warring factions) divergent positions,
progress has been slow," he noted.
</P>
<P>
"Nevertheless, we are encouraged to find the fact that all the
parties concerned appreciated Pakistan's peace initiatives and
assured their cooperation and have asked us to continue our
efforts," he said.
</P>
<P>
When asked if Pakistan has got close to an intra-Afghan
dialogue, the spokesman said: "It would be realistic to say we've
got close to but our efforts will continue."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman also announced at the weekly news briefing that
Japanese Foreign Minister Yukihiko Ikeda will visit Pakistan from
July 21 to 23.
</P>
<P>
During Ikeda's visit, the focus of talks will be on the
strengthening of economic and commercial ties between Pakistan and
Japan, he said, adding that the two sides will sign three
agreements concerning Japanese development assistance to Pakistan.
</P>
<P>
</P>
