<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan's Trade Surplus up 28.4 Percent in First Six Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Japan's merchandise trade surplus in
the first half of this year increased 28.4 percent to 3,981.9
billion yen (about 35.2 billion U.S. dollars) from the
year-earlier level, boosted by exports of automobiles and office
equipment, the Finance Ministry said today.
</P>
<P>
This is the first upturn since the first half of 1993, when the
surplus rose 5.3 percent, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The trade surplus for June rose 27.7 percent from a year
earlier to 934.21 billion yen (8.3 billion dollars), up for the
third consecutive month.
</P>
<P>
In the January-June period, exports increased 15.1 percent to
24,729.4 billion yen (218.8 billion dollars), while imports rose
12.9 percent to 20,747.5 billion yen (183.6 billion dollars), the
ministry said.
</P>
<P>
Japan's trade surplus with the United States increased 48.8
percent to 2,234 billion yen (19.8 billion dollars), up for the
second straight six-month period.
</P>
<P>
In trade with the U.S., exports rose 18.9 percent to 6,915.6
billion yen (61.2 billion dollars), while imports edged up 8.5
percent to 4,681.6 billion yen (42 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
Japan also posted increases in its trade surplus with the
European Union (EU) and Asia due to growing exports to those
areas.
</P>
<P>
The surplus with the EU expanded 43.9 percent to 1,048.8
billion yen (9.3 billion dollars), the first rise since the second
half of 1992, while that with Asian countries marked a surplus of
2,917.8 billion yen (25.8 billion dollars), up 9.4 percent for the
first rise since the second half of 1995.
</P>
<P>
As for Japan's global trade in June, exports increased 12.5
percent to 4,119.42 billion yen (36.5 billion dollars), while
imports totaled 3,185.21 billion yen (28.2 billion dollars), up
8.7 percent from the previous month.
</P>
<P>
"Favorable exports of automobiles and office supplies have
brought about double-digit growth for the sixth consecutive month,
while the April 1 consumption tax hike has capped the rises of
imports of automobiles and clothes," an official from the Finance
Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
"We can not say how long the consumption tax will continue
affecting Japan's global trade," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
