<HEADLINE> Australian Dollar Takes Break from Downward March </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, July 17 (Xinhua) -- The Australian dollar took a
break from its steady decline today, closing higher against the
U.S. currency after a day of reasonable bidding.
</P>
<P>
The local unit finished at 73.67 U.S. cents, up from 73.25
Wednesday, and near today's high of 73.78 U.S. cents.
</P>
<P>
Westpac Bank's manager of foreign exchange, Wayne Raven, said
the Australian dollar had run into some buying interest across the
board which had offered it support.
</P>
<P>
He said while the local currency was having difficulty reaching
the 73.80 cents level today, it may well move higher in offshore
trading tonight.
</P>
<P>
Ongoing speculation of an easing in monetary policy by the
Reserve Bank of Australia (RBA) by the end of August remains the
dominant factor for the local currency.
</P>
<P>
There has been some sentiment in the market that if the
Australian dollar continues to slide, the RBA may not move to cut
rates in the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
On the cross-rates, the Australian dollar ended at 85.53
Japanese yen, up from 84.55, and at 1.3252 German marks, up from
1.3118.  
</P>
</TEXT>
