-- According to the Belgian political scientist Joel Kotek, the
French-speaking Walloon part of Belgium is experiencing a deep
identity crisis worsened by an economic crisis, as most of the
common historic and cultural patrimony of Belgium is taken by the
northern Dutch-speaking Flemish part of the country. The only
surviving myth to keep together the Walloons is the comic strip
hero Tintin, designed by Georges Remi Herge, he said.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro:
</P>
<P>
-- Prime Minister Lionel Jospin will chair today a cabinet
session to examine how to keep the budget in balance in
anticipation of an announcement on July 21 by a public finance
audit on France's public deficit this year, which is expected to
be around 3.5 percent of gross domestic product. The way for
Jospin to reduce the deficit is most probably to impose "euro
taxes" on enterprises and wealthy families.
</P>
<P>
-- Prime Minister Jospin retorted Wednesday the attacks made by
President Jacques Chirac upon his policies on Bastille Day, saying
that he has the "constitutional prerogatives" to decide his
policies. During a television interview on Monday, Chirac
criticized the policies of Jospin on family allowances,
privatizations, and immigration. 
</P>
