<HEADLINE> Britain to Open Debate on Single European Currency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Britain's Chancellor of the
Exchequer Gordon Brown is to launch later today a serious national
debate on the implications of the planned single European currency
due to be implemented on January 1 1999.
</P>
<P>
Brown is likely to reaffirm the Labor government's view that
there remain "formidable obstacles" to Britain's signing up to the
first wave of the European Monetary Union (EMU), according to a
report in today's Daily Telegraph.
</P>
<P>
The Chancellor will tell a London gathering: "The Prime
Minister (Tony Blair) and the Government believe that time has
come for a serious debate about Economic and Monetary Union."
</P>
<P>
"Whether Britain is in or out (of the first wave), EMU will
have profound implications for British business and the British
economy."
</P>
<P>
He will also stress that the British government's current
position is that it is keeping its options open, but will make it
clear that there should be no "fudging" of the strict economic
criteria for the single currency, euro.
</P>
<P>
Political analysts said that the a national debate on the
single currency, which has put an end to an 18-year Conservative
government, will revive the fiercest political controversy over
the past five years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
