<DOCNO> XIE19970717.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand's Interest Rate Caps Likely to be Eased </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 17 (Xinhua) -- The Bank of Thailand is
considering easing interest rate controls on local financial
institutions to reflect economic and market realities.
</P>
<P>
The cap on deposit rates for commercial banks and finance
companies was established on June 30 and was aimed at stemming the
transfer of public deposits after the authorities announced the
suspension of 16 ailing finance and securities companies.
</P>
<P>
The deposit interest rate cap for commercial banks was set at
12 percent and 14 percent for finance companies.
</P>
<P>
Bank of Thailand deputy governor Jaroong Nookwun said Wednesday
that the authorities were prepared to adjust the interest rate
caps to reflect market needs.
</P>
<P>
He said deposit interest rates should not be too high, as this
would increase the funding costs of local financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
Olarn chaipravat, president of the Thai Bankers' Association,
said lifitng the ceiling would almost certainly result in
commercial banks raising rates, reflecting the tight liquidity in
the money market.
</P>
<P>
Average inter-finance rates currently stand at 20-25 percent,
he said, adding that mobilizing funds from the public would thus
prove cheaper than borrowing in the money market.
</P>
<P>
With increased capital inflow as a result of a cheaper baht,
local interest rates would be able to drop, although this would
likely take up to one year, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970717.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia: No Slave Conditions For Workers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, July 17 (Xinhua) -- The Zambian government has said it
will not allow any investors to subject workers to slave
conditions, Times of Zambia reported today.
</P>
<P>
According to the local newspaper, Commerce, Trade and
Industry Minister Alfeyo Hambayi made the satement here Wednesday
to ease the fears expressed by labor leaders of the country that
Zambian workers will be subjected to inhuman work conditions
under the proposed Export Processing Zones (EPZ).
</P>
<P>
The intention of introducing the EPZ is to create employment
through industrialization, enhanced exports for subsequent
economic development, but some union leaders have expressed their
concern over the slavery the EPZ has brought to some other
African countries and hoped it will not be so in Zambia.
</P>
<P>
The government will soon prescribe a minimum wage for workers
to check excessive exploitative tendencies among employers.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this week Labor Minister Peter Machungwa inspected
some business premises founding some employers offering their
workers too low salaries and breaching labor laws including
workers' rights, and occupational health regulations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
