<HEADLINE> Turkey to Buy 10 Cargo Choppers from US </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Turkey is planning to buy 10
Sihorsky-made cargo helicopters from the United States in an
effort to enhance the capability of its special forces.
</P>
<P>
Local newspaper Daily News today quoted high-ranking military
sources, who asked not to be named, as saying that these cargo
helicopters would be purchased under the U.S. Surplus Arms
Program.
</P>
<P>
The sources said that the cargo helicopters would be modified
in Israel or in Turkey with the assistance of Israeli Aircraft
Industries.
</P>
<P>
They said that the modification, including the equipment of
night-vision systems, would adequate these choppers to Turkey's
specifications.
</P>
<P>
The deal to buy the helicopters, which are being used by
U.S. special forces, was made during the visits of Turkey's
Deputy Chief of General Staff Cevik Bir to Israel and the U.S..
He has reportedly insisted on buying such helicopters from
Washington.
</P>
<P>
Turkey is among the first three of countries which buy
U.S. surplus arms, according to an earlier defense report.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish military have long been demanding heavy-lifting
helicopters in a bid to support their routine military operations
against outlawed Kurdish Worker's Party (PKK) rebels in
southeastern region or possible massive cross-border incursion
in norther Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The Sikorsky Black Hawks and Eurocopter Cougars, which the
Turkish Army currently use, are both designed for light lifting
and personnel transport. 
</P>
</TEXT>
