<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Leading Petrochemical Industrial Base Taking Shape Near Meizhou Bay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, July 17 (Xinhua) -- A leading petrochemical industrial
base is taking shape on the southern bank of Meizhou Bay, located
in east China's Fujian Province.
</P>
<P>
Xiaocuo Economic and Technological Development Zone, which is
connected to other parts of the country by two expressways and one
railway line, has expanded a group of petrochemical industrial
projects, and finished site selection and land lease work for more
petrochemical projects in the zone.
</P>
<P>
The development zone, which has an area of 319 sq km and a
population of 350,000, has a 5.5-km-long deep-water coastline
where berths with handling capacity of more than 300,000 tons can
be built.
</P>
<P>
So far, the development zone has finished construction of one
sundry goods berth and two berths for petroleum and oil-related
commodities. It has been constructing one container berth, one
grain berth, one coal berth and one oil-related berth.
</P>
<P>
The management committee for the zone, which started business
one year ago, has been given some of the economic management power
and preferential policies enjoyed by a city directly administered
by the provincial government.
</P>
<P>
The zone authorities have set a goal to build it into a port
city with the petrochemical industry as a dominant business.
</P>
<P>
The zone has also made efforts to improve its infrastructure
and a group of such projects have been finished in recent years.
</P>
<P>
By June of this year, the zone had approved the establishment
of 43 overseas-backed businesses, with overseas investors putting
up 120 million U.S. dollars for the projects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
