<DOCNO> XIE19970717.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 5 Drug Dealers Hanged in Public in Iran </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Five men charged with drug
smuggling have been hanged recently in public in the border town
of Sarakhs, about 900 kilometers east of Tehran, a local daily
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The Persian daily Jomhuri Islami reported that local government
officials, Friday prayer leaders and residents gathered at a
public square to witness the hanging. But the report gave no date
of the hanging.
</P>
<P>
The five drug dealers were charged with armed clashes with
police as well as smuggling opium, unlawful carrying of arms,
ammunition and wireless items.
</P>
<P>
The five criminals were identified as Rahmatollah Bashti-Niya,
Zaher Esma'eeli, Ayd Mohammad Dadmohammad Khani, Abassali
Sheikhzadeh and Ne'matollah Sarani.
</P>
<P>
Their execution was ordered by the Revolutionary Court in
northeastern province of Khorassan, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The Revolutionary Court was set up in Iran after the Islamic
Revolution of 1979. The verdicts handed down by the court can not
be appealed.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian government recently declared that while it showed
compassion to the drug addicts, it showed no mercy to drug
dealers.
</P>
<P>
Interior Minister Ali Mohammad Besharati has said "if someone
is found with 30 grams of heroin or five kg of opium he will be
condemned to death by execution."
</P>
<P>
According to an official report, 35 tonnes of narcotics were
seized by Iranian armed policemen in the first three months of the
current Iranian calendar year starting from March 21, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Iranian armed policemen confiscated 191 tonnes of narcotics
from the drug dealers during the last Iranian calendar year
ending on March 20, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Iran is used as a transit route for the narcotic produced
in Afghanistan and Pakistan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
