<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0900 GMT, July 17 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA -- Indonesian Foreign Minister Ali Alatas said here
Wednesday that the Association of Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN)
does not intend to propose anything that would settle Cambodia's
internal crisis.
</P>
<P>
"We go to Beijing without bringing any recipe. We merely want
to hear Sihanouk's views on the efforts to settle the Cambodian
conflict," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- A senior Iraqi diplomat has said that Iraq attaches
great importance to its relations with Turkey and wants closer
Iraqi-Turkish cooperation, local newspaper Daily News reported
today.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview with the paper on the occasion of
Iraq's 29th anniversary of national day on July 14, Iraqi Charge
d'affaires Saad Al-Samarrai said that Iraq regards Ankara as one
of its most important partners.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Israeli troops have closed off all
Palestinian-controlled cities in the West Bank to Israelis for
security reasons, Israel Radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The closure affected the cities of Bethlehem, Hebron,
Ramallah, Jericho, Kalkilya, Tulkarm and Nablus. Israeli troops
took the action following Monday's arrest of three Palestinian
policemen.
</P>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG -- De Beers Consolidated Mines (DBCM), the South
African diamond giant, has reached an agreement with the Guinean
government over mining in the western African country, said
informed sources reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, De Beers Centenary, the offshore diamond
arms of DBCM, will be allowed to manage any mine it explores in
Guinea.
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto said
Thursday that he will soon order the Defense Agency to withdraw
three transport planes of the Air Self-Defense Force (ASDF) from
Thailand, Kyodo News reported.
</P>
<P>
The three C-130H transport planes are currently standing by in
Thailand for possible evacuation of Japanese nationals from
Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
HAVANA -- The Cuban authorities Wednesday ruled out sabotage as
the cause of Friday's air disaster which killed 44 people.
</P>
<P>
The most probable cause of the crash of a Cubana de Aviation
airplane was a mechanical failure which paralyzed the left engine,
a statement issued by the Cuban Civil Aeronautical Institute said.
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov said
Wednesday Russia remains opposed to NATO's eastward expansion and
this position will not change.
</P>
<P>
"Russia will not change its stand on opposing NATO's eastward
expansion," Primakov told visiting journalists from leading
Japanese newspapers.
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- Representatives of different regions,
countries and UN agencies Wednesday expressed appreciation to
Secretary-General Kofi Annan's UN reform proposals.
</P>
<P>
Jacob Wilmot of Ghana, on behalf of the African states, said
that the overall aim of reform was to make the Organization more
efficient, relevant and effective to be able to fulfil better its
core principles and purposes of promoting peace and security,
economic prosperity, social progress, humanitarian assistance and
overall development; and also to deal with current and future
challenges as the international community entered the new
millennium.
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The United Nations agencies welcomed and
voiced full support for the U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan's
reform proposals announced before the General Assembly Wednesday
morning.
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- Secretary-General Kofi Annan announced
Wednesday before the United Nations General Assembly his
recommendations for the reform of the UN budgeting system, calling
for a new one with solvency and development priorities.
</P>
<P>
The Secretary-General proposes to the General Assembly a small
budget for the period of 1998-1999 as compared to the 1997-1998
period. This will be the first time in a generation there has been
negative growth, in real terms, in the United Nations budget.
</P>
</TEXT>
