<HEADLINE> Philippines' De Villa Says People Would Vote for Him </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Philippine Defense Secretary Renato
de Villa said today that he believed the Filipinos would vote for
him in the 1998 presidential election.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a luncheon with foreign correspondents based here,
he said: "I believe that I know all the people. I believe that I
know all their problems. I believe that I could do very much to
help them and our country."
</P>
<P>
De villa said he could offer to the Filipinos a leadership that
could provide continuity in the basic reform and the programs of
the current government that have been proven successful and
beneficial to the people.
</P>
<P>
"Being a non-traditional politician, I believe that I will be
able to respond to many of our people's needs and desires in the
matter of the kind of government they want," he said.
</P>
<P>
De Villa also disclosed that if elected, he would not make
basic changes to the country's current foreign and economic
policies.
</P>
<P>
But he said he would strengthen campaigns against crimes,
better the country's justice system, take efforts to reduce
poverty and improve the quality of the people's life.
</P>
<P>
De Villa is one of the six presidential aspirants within the
ruling Lakas-NUCD party. He and House Speaker Jose de Venecia have
been described by local media as the most hopefuls in the 1998
polls.
</P>
<P>
The military chief said he and other aspirants had been
informed that President Fidel Ramos wants to see them on Friday.
During the meeting, all aspirants would meet for the first time a
15-member committee set up by Ramos to choose his successor.
</P>
<P>
However, Ramos has said he would not reveal his choice to the
public before the party's national convention in November this
year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
