<HEADLINE> PNA: UN Resolution on Settlement an Arab Victory </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian permanent delegate to
the United Nations Nasser Al Koddwah today hailed the U.N.
resolution urging an end to Israeli settlement activities in
the Palestinian lands "a victory for the Arab party."
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Egyptian Voice of Arabs radio this morning,
Koddwah called for the continuation of the U.N. General Assembly
emergency session to follow up the issue.
</P>
<P>
For the third time, the General Assembly Tuesday voted
overwhelmingly to condemn Israel's failure to stop a housing
project in Jerusalem and urged member states to discourage
activities that contribute to Jewish settlements.
</P>
<P>
The approval of the resolution by 131 states is regarded a
victory for the Arab party, he added.
</P>
<P>
"The Palestinian delegate reiterated the significance of the
U.N. resolution from the legal and political aspects as it will
help increase Israel's isolation internationally," he said.
</P>
<P>
The resolution, though shy away from ordering economic
sanctions against Israel, is considered by Arabs an important step
in keeping up international pressure against Israel's decision to
build the Har Homa settlement in East Jerusalem, where the
Palestinians want as their future capital.
</P>
<P>
The non-binding resolution, tabled by Arab and Muslim
countries, was approved by 131 countries, with the U.S., Israel
and Micronesia Islands opposing and 14 others, including Russia,
abstaining.
</P>
<P>
"Both the U.S. and Israel have launched a ferocious campaign to
hinder the issuance of this resolution. But the Arab side led by
Egypt had succeeded in rendering its issuance," said the
Palestinian official.
</P>
<P>
Although the U.S. vote of objection is "very strange" in its
capacity as a key Mideast peace sponsor, the Arab side is still
hoping that the U.S. would play a balanced role and give up its
bias to Israel.
</P>
<P>
But Israel said it would not bow to what it called "false
international pressure" and the U.S. warned the resolution would
undermine rather than build the peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970717.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flourishing Economic Growth in Rural Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Economic development in rural
Shanghai recorded a sustained and rapid growth in the first half
of this year.
</P>
<P>
The Gross Domestic Product (GDP) in the suburbs of Shanghai
totalled 40.7 billion yuan in the first six months, 18.7 percent
higher than the same period of last year. Its revenue rose 18.8
percent at 6.19 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Local farmers have harvested 580,000 tons of wheat from 138,600
ha of land, a 4.5-percent rise over last year. The supply of
non-staple food and vegetables is ample and the price remained
stable.
</P>
<P>
The industrial output value from sales in the suburbs came to
98.6 billion yuan in the first half, up 23 percent, while the
industrial profit surged 30 percent at 2.7 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The export value increased by 30 percent to reach 18.5 billion
yuan.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, farmers have more cash in hand and the remaining sum
of the savings deposit at the end of June grew by 25 percent to
hit 58.2 billion yuan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
