<HEADLINE> Foreign Funds Bring New Initiatives Into China's Road Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Road workers have been braving the
burning sun to finish the Shanghai section of an east China
expressway between Shanghai, China's largest business center, and
Hangzhou, capital city of Zhejiang Province.
</P>
<P>
Of the total 2.1 billion yuan to be invested in the project, 60
million US dollars (around 500 million yuan) will come from the
World Bank, marking the first time that Shanghai has used foreign
funds for a road project.
</P>
<P>
An official with the Ministry of Communications said that since
1985, the year China introduced World Bank loans for road
projects, a dozen Chinese provinces, autonomous regions and
municipalities have spent some five billion US dollars building
over 10,000 km of highways.
</P>
<P>
The adoption of foreign funds in road construction has not only
accelerated the construction of highways in China, but also brought
about enormous changes in the sector as a whole in terms of
bidding, management and supervision, according to the official.
</P>
<P>
China has sent a large number of professionals such as
engineers, managers and accountants to advanced countries for
further study. Meanwhile, foreign experts have been invited to
offer training courses for Chinese.
</P>
<P>
Till now, over 800 people have studied overseas and over 1,400
have been trained at home, according to official figures.
</P>
<P>
China has used foreign loans to purchase hi-tech equipment
worth over 60 million US dollars and also has carried out a number
of research projects to solve some urgent problems plaguing
the country's road sector.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
