<HEADLINE> Holidayers Tour on China-aided Tanzania-Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 17 (Xinhua) -- The South African vintage
train - Rovos Rail - arrived in Dar es Salaam again through the
Tanzania-Zambia Railway (TAZARA) Wednesday with 52 tourists from
six countries, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
The vintage train commonly known as "the Pride of Africa"
arrived at the TAZARA Dar es Salaam station Wednesday from Cape
Town, South Africa, where it commenced the annual journey on July
5.
</P>
<P>
It is the third time for the train to come in Tanzania through
TAZARA.
</P>
<P>
Roban Vos, the train proprietor, told reporters at the Dar es
Salaam station that the tourists will visit Tanzania before
leaving for other destinations over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
Some of them will visit various tourist sites on the Mainland
and Zanzibar in the country, Nairobi and the Maasai Mara Game
Reserve in Kenya, he said.
</P>
<P>
The train is made of old refurbished coaches in use by South
African Railways since late last century. They are meant to
attract wealthy holiday makers wishing to use classic, pleasant
old coaches into first rate luxury hotel standard.
</P>
<P>
On its way from Cape Town to Dar es Salaam, the train passed
through famous historical sites in South Africa, Zimbabwe and
Zambia before entering Tanzania Tunduma on the border between the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
The investor commenced the annual rolling mission to Tanzania
four years ago on a tourism promotional campaign to make Tanzania
known in the South Africa tourism market and excite interest
among classical train enthusiasts the world over, explained the
South African train proprietor.
</P>
<P>
The train covers some 6,100 kilometers from Cape Town to Dar
es Salaam, of which 1860 kilometers are covered through TAZARA
built with the Chinese assistance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
