<HEADLINE> Indonesian PM: ASEAN Has No 'Recipe' for Cambodia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Indonesian Foreign Minister Ali
Alatas said here Wednesday that the Association of Southeast Asian
Nations (ASEAN) does not intend to propose anything that would
settle Cambodia's internal crisis.
</P>
<P>
"We go to Beijing without bringing any recipe. We merely want
to hear Sihanouk's views on the efforts to settle the Cambodian
conflict," the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Alatas, along with foreign ministers of Thailand and the
Philippines, Prachuab Chaiyasarn and Domingo Siazon, is expected
to meet Cambodian King Norodom Sihanouk, who is now in Beijing for
a medical treatment, on Thursday on the Cambodian crisis.
</P>
<P>
The Indonesian minister said he will continue his visit to
Bangkok, Thailand, to meet the Cambodian First Prime Minister
Prince Norodom Ranariddh after talking with the king.
</P>
<P>
"I hope I could be in Phnom Penh as soon as possible to meet
with Cambodian Second Prime Minister Hun Sen after that," he added.
</P>
<P>
At a special meeting in Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia, on July 10,
ASEAN decided to postpone Cambodia's admission to the group until
a date to be fixed later.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also agreed to send Alatas, Siazon and Chaiyasarn
to meet Sihanouk as part of an effort to help solve the Cambodian
conflict.
</P>
<P>
Cambodia, along with Laos and Myanmar, is slated to become a
full member of ASEAN during the 30th ministerial meeting on July
24-25 in Kuala Lumpur.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN groups Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines,
Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam. 
</P>
