<HEADLINE> Diplomat: Iraq Wants Closer Ties With Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, July 17 (Xinhua) -- A senior Iraqi diplomat has said
that Iraq attaches great importance to its relations with Turkey
and wants closer Iraqi-Turkish cooperation, local newspaper Daily
News reported today.
</P>
<P>
In an exclusive interview with the paper on the occasion of
Iraq's 29th anniversary of national day on July 14, Iraqi Charge
d'affaires Saad Al-Samarrai said that Iraq regards Ankara as one
of its most important partners.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the brotherly relations between the two
countries are based on the friendly affection between the peoples,
adding the bilateral ties should not be subject to the change of
leaders.
</P>
<P>
"Relations between Turkey and Iraq should be at the highest
possible level in view of our historical and cultural
relations. We expect a greater effort on the part of Turkey both
in the economic and political fields, " Al-Samarrai said.
</P>
<P>
The diplomat, however, also expressed his disappointment with
the current situation of the relations of the two neighboring
nations.
</P>
<P>
Complaining that Turkey failed to give more support to the
U.N. sanctions-hit country, Al-Samarrai stressed that this caused
great loss to both countries.
</P>
<P>
Since the implementation of the oil-for-food agreement reached
between U.N. and Iraqi government, Turkey won only a small part of
the food contracts with Iraq due to its high prices.
</P>
<P>
On the Kurdish issue, Al-Samarrai denied the press reports
that the Baghdad administration was trying to play a Kurdish card
against Turkey.
</P>
<P>
"Turkey is strategically important for Baghdad. If Turkey is
hurt, Iraq will also be hurt. We will never play any PKK (Kurdish
Workers' Party) card against Ankara," he said.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that Baghdad is against any forms of international
terrorism including "the actions of PKK."
</P>
<P>
Turkey ordered a large-scale cross-border military campaign on
May 14 in northern Iraq to wipe out the outlawed PKK rebels
there, drawing strong opposition from the Iraqi government and
other Arab and Western countries as well.
</P>
<P>
The official said that there are great potentials for the
Iraqi-Turkish economic cooperation, but the ball is in Ankara's
court. 
</P>
</TEXT>
