<HEADLINE> Tanzania Builds 25 Street Kids Centers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Twenty-five street children
centers in 11 towns have been established so as to control the
growing problem of street children in Tanzania, local press
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Answering a question concerned at the National Assembly in
Dodoma, central Tanzania Wednesday, the Deputy Minister for
Labour and Youth Development, William Lukuvi, said the projects
were in Arusha, Dar es Salaam, Dodoma, Mwanza and some other
towns.
</P>
<P>
The deputy minister acknowledged the prevalence of the problem
but said that it was on an increase because of social problems
facing the country.
</P>
<P>
He said the problem emerged for the first time in 1986 when a
lot of children were spotted loitering in streets in big towns
like Dar es Salaam, Arusha and Mwanza.
</P>
<P>
To understand the dimensions of the problem, Lukuvi said his
ministry did a research in Dar es Salaam way back in 1990. The
research revealed that the city had about 350 street children, he
added.
</P>
<P>
The deputy minister said the research also showed that among
the reasons forcing children into street life were economic
hardships in their families and the break up of their parents'
marriages.
</P>
<P>
Lukuvi said the establishment of the street children centers,
run by religious organizations and individuals, was one of the
strategies intended to curb or reduce the problem of street
children.
</P>
<P>
He also said the ministry would co-ordinate all street
children projects and provide counselling and guidance to enable
families bring up children well and provide them with basic
necessities.
</P>
<P>
The deputy minister said that the government would strengthen
children day-care centers, fight for children rights and
intensify efforts to take care of orphans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
