<HEADLINE> Israel Clamps Closure on Palestinian Cities in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Israeli troops have closed off
all Palestinian-controlled cities in the West Bank to Israelis
for security reasons, Israel Radio reported today.
</P>
<P>
The closure affected the cities of Bethlehem, Hebron,
Ramallah, Jericho, Kalkilya, Tulkarm and Nablus. Israeli troops
took the action following Monday's arrest of three Palestinian
policemen, who allegedly attempted to carry out a shooting
attack against the Har Bracha settlement near Nablus.
</P>
<P>
Israeli security establishment decided to bar Israelis from
entering the Palestinian cities because of fears about possible
revenge taken by Palestinians on Israelis, the radio said.
</P>
<P>
Israeli senior political and military officials took advantage
of the incident by lauching verbal attacks on the Palestinian
National Authority (PNA) to pressure it to crack down on
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy accused Wednesday the PNA
police of fomenting and inciting anti-Israeli violence instead
of quelling it. Levy said Israeli seucirty forces could react
severely to Heborn's Palestinian rioters, but they preferred to
exercise restraint as long as the city's Jewish residents were
not endangered.
</P>
<P>
Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai raised the issue of the
Palestinian policemen during his overnight meeting with PNA
Planning Minister Nabil Shaath at the residence of Egyptian
Ambassador Mohammed Bassiouny near Tel Aviv. Mordechai demanded
the PNA take urgent steps to prevent the repetition of such
incident.
</P>
<P>
Army Chief of Staff Amnon Shahak, who toured Hebron late
Wednesday, also strongly blasted the PNA for ordering attacks on
Israelis, like the one stymied at Har Bracha Monday. He demanded
the PNA arrest Palestinian police's Assistant Commander Jihad
Masini, who was blamed by Israel for being behind the attack
plot.
</P>
<P>
"I hope that a clarification of the matter (will lead to)
steps they must take to understand how this sort of thing was
possible," Shahak said.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian side has not yet responded to the Israeli
claims and demands concerning the arrest of three Palestinian
policemen. But in recent days, Palestinian police played a more
active role in preventing Palestinian rioters from attacking
Israeli soldiers in Hebron, helping calm down the tense situation
in the wake of recent waves of violence.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, 2,000 Palestinian mouners attended Wednesday the
funeral in Beit Sahur, south of Jerusalem, of a 16-year-old
Palestinian who was shot in the head with a rubber bullet by
Israeli soldiers Monday and died of the wounds later.
</P>
<P>
The funeral later turned violent as Palestinian mourners
stoned an Israeli police patrol, injuring one of the border
policeman. Israeli soldiers responded with rubber bullets and
tear gas to disperse the rioters and arrested two of them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
