<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 17 (Xinhua) -- A train transporting diesel
derailed Wednesday at a station in Swartruggens, North West
Province, rocking the area with powerful explosions, South
African Press Association (SAPA) reported today.
</P>
<P>
The train was transporting 1,140 tons of diesel to Ndola,
Zambia, from the port city of Durban, South Africa, SAPA quoted
informed sources as reporting.
</P>
<P>
The thundering explosions sent flames 150 meters up into the
sky, witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
No casualty is reported yet, they said, but at least one house
beside the railway line caught fire and a local post office, a
telephone exchange house, a number of businesses and railway
houses had to be evacuated as thick white smoke smothered the
town.
</P>
<P>
A spokesman for the railway department said the train was
travelling at the "normal" speed of 30 km/h when the accident
happened. He blamed a possible faulty rail flange for the
accident.
</P>
<P>
The inferno was eventually brought under control late at
Wednesday night. 
</P>
