<HEADLINE> ***** ************************************************************************ Missing Lesser Panda Back Home Safe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DALIAN, July 17 (Xinhua) -- A missing allurnsfuigens, or Lesser
Panda, missing for 45 days from the Forest Zoo of Dalian, has been
brought back home safely.
</P>
<P>
The four-year-old panda, said by zookeepers to be one of the
naughtiest of the 16 at the zoo, was apparently annoyed by the
noise made by workers repairing his cage and disappeared on May
26.
</P>
<P>
Two local residents from this port city in northeast China's
Liaoning Province spotted him on July 10 sitting on a tree near
the beach in the southern part of the city.
</P>
<P>
The missing panda was immediately reported to police. Four
policemen and the two residents kept watch under the tree until
panda-catchers from the zoo arrived. They spread a net under the
tree for the panda to jump into.
</P>
<P>
Though a good deal slimmer than before, the panda seems to have
a good appetite. Lesser pandas live on bamboo shoots, fruit and
small animals.
</P>
<P>
Zookeepers said that the panda was able to survive such a long
time on his own thanks to a bamboo forest in the southeast of the
zoo and a lake nearby.
</P>
<P>
"It was not difficult for the panda to find food and
water. That's lucky for him," they said.
</P>
<P>
The Lesser Panda, with yellow, white and black stripes, is now
under second-class government protection. It lives in the forests
in southwest China.  
</P>
</TEXT>
