<HEADLINE> Trade Deficit Continues to Narrow in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 17 (Xinhua) -- The trade deficit in the
Philippines decreased by 11.5 percent in May this year with the
rise in the country's exports, the National Statistics Office said
today.
</P>
<P>
In a report released here, the office said that the trade
deficit dropped by 11.5 percent to 973 million U.S. dollars from
1.1 billion dollars during the same period of 1996.
</P>
<P>
"Merchandise trade for May 1997 grew by 14.2 percent
year-on-year to 4.939 billion dollars from 4.324 billion dollars.
Imports valued at 2.956 billion dollars grew by 9 percent from
2.712 billion dollars, while exports rose by 23 percent to 1.983
billion dollars from 1.612 billion dollars," the office said.
</P>
<P>
The year-on-year trade deficit in the Philippines has been
declining since March this year.
</P>
<P>
The April trade deficit declined nearly 35 percent to 860
million dollars from 1.3 billion dollars a year earlier, when
exports jumped 40 percent to 2 billion dollars in the month.
</P>
<P>
For the first five months of this year, the office said,
imports increased by 11 percent while exports rose by 22.9
percent.
</P>
<P>
The government is targeting a 24 percent export growth for the
full year though some economists do not expect the figure to
exceed 20 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
