<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam to Develop Bus System in Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, July 17 (xinhua) -- Vietnam plans to develop public bus
system in Hanoi in order to meet 35-40 percent of the demand of
the Hanoian commuters by the year 2000, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Under the plan, Hanoi will invest 52 million U.S. dollars
between now and 2000 to buy 1,400 buses, upgrade bus stops and
related facilities, and to increase bus lines from 13 in 1997 to
58 by the end of 1998 and 66 by 2000.
</P>
<P>
The network of bus routes and timetables will be improved so
that passengers will have to wait less than ten minutes and spend
less than ten percent of their monthly income on ticket fares.
</P>
<P>
Among transport means now used by Hanoians, motor bikes account
for 60 percent, bicycles 30 percent, buses three percent, and
three-wheeled taxis 1.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
Hanoi covers 927 square kilometers and has a population of 2.4
million. In 20 years' time, its area is expected to expand by 170
percent, and its population will increase to 4.5 million. 
</P>
</TEXT>
