<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-17 07:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli, Palestinian Officials Meet to Solve </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Defense Minister
Yitzhak Mordechai met with Palestinian National Authority (PNA)
Planning Minister Nabil Shaath Wednesday night in a bid to pave
the way for reviving the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The two officials held the meeting at the residence of
Egyptian ambassador in Tel Aviv, Mohammed Bassiouny, in Herzliya
Pituah, near Tel Aviv, in the presence of the United States
Ambassador Martin Indyk.
</P>
<P>
This was the second meeting held by Mordechai and Shaath at the
same place in less than two weeks.
</P>
<P>
No details of the meeting were disclosed, but Israel Radio
reported that the two sides discussed the unsolved issues on
opening the Gaza airport and seaport, building "safe passages"
between the West Bank and Gaza Strip and the release of more
Palestinian detainees by Israel.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to Palestinian reporters before the meeting, Shaath
said he did not expect much from the meeting. He called it the
"last chance" to prevent a disaster, which would occur if there
was no further progress in the talks.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Mordechai expressed concern about the recent
disclosure that three Palestinian policemen were caught red-handed
during an attempt to attack a Jewish settlement.
</P>
<P>
He told Shaath that the PNA should take urgent steps to
prevent the recurrence of such incidents.
</P>
<P>
Israel announced Tuesday that its security forces arrested
three Palestinian policemen on Monday night in their attempt to
carry out a shooting attack on the settlement of Har Bracha on
Mount Grizim, overlooking Nablus.
</P>
<P>
During their first meeting a week ago, Mordechai and
Shaath made some progress on the issues of opening the Gaza
airport and seaport.
</P>
<P>
Later officials from both sides reached agreement on naming
the Dahaniya airport as the Gaza International Airport and on the
taking-off and landing procedures of the airport.
</P>
<P>
But the two sides still failed to solve the thorny issues of
security arrangements, as Israel insists on controlling the
security checks in order to prevent the PNA from using the
airport and seaport for getting weapons that could threaten
Israel's security.
</P>
<P>
If the two sides resolved the remaining differences, it could
pave the way for resuming the Israeli-Palestinian peace
negotiations that have been frozen since March when Israel began
building the Har Homa settlement in East Jerusalem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
