<DOCNO> XIE19970717.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dar Port to Go Commercial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, July 17 (Xinhua) -- The container and grain
terminals at the Dar es Salaam port will be commercialized in the
first phase of a three-year plan to restructure the Tanzania
Harbors Authority (THA).
</P>
<P>
The THA Acting Director General, Peter Mtandu, said here
Wednesday that the business units would operate autonomously
under the restructuring aimed at making the authority a landlord
port.
</P>
<P>
He said under a commercialization study completed last August,
which has been endorsed by the government, the THA would continue
owning the port infrastructure but would no longer have a role in
direct operations.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the container and grain terminals, the plan is to
make the general cargo, bulk liquid, coastal terminals, and the
Tanga and Mtwara ports go into joint venture or lease.
</P>
<P>
Mtandu was presenting a paper at a three-day workshop on port
commercialization jointly organized by the Economic Commission
for Africa, Economic Commission for Latin America and Port
Management Association of Eastern and Southern Africa, being held
in the city.
</P>
<P>
"THA will progress into privatization in stages by having a
transitional period in order to avoid crisis as well as avail
itself time of upgrading its different business units to a level
where private operators will be compelled to give a fair
compensation for managing and operating the facilities," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Mtandu, there was a compelling need to involve
the private sector in port operations in developing countries
like Tanzania to perform efficiently and effectively.
</P>
<P>
"The plan drawn for THA envisages that by the year 2000
operational activities will have been separated from the
regulatory and ownership framework and the private sector playing
a leading role," the acting general manager said.
</P>
<P>
Mtandu said although THA's performance has improved
considerably, particularly with regard to containerized traffic,
the need for restructuring the corporation was imperative because
of the competitive environment in port operations.
</P>
<P>
The workshop, which is being hosted by THA, was opened by the
Principal Secretary in the Ministry of Communications and
Transport, Salim Msoma. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
