<HEADLINE> S. African Diamond Giant to Mine in Guinea </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, July 17 (Xinhua) -- De Beers Consolidated Mines
(DBCM), the South African diamond giant, has reached an agreement
with the Guinean government over mining in the western African
country, said informed sources reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, De Beers Centenary, the offshore diamond
arms of DBCM, will be allowed to manage any mine it explores in
Guinea.
</P>
<P>
The accord also provides for diamonds produced at any new
mines to be sold through the Central Selling Organization (CSO),
De Beers' diamond purchasing and marketing arms, the sources
said.
</P>
<P>
De Beers has been prospecting for kimberlites -- hard rock
deposits generally considered likely to contain diamonds -- in
Guinea since 1995.
</P>
<P>
The CSO reportedly operates two buying offices in Conakry and
Kankan. The buying offices purchase rough diamonds produced at
mines around Guinea. 
</P>
