<HEADLINE> East China Province Doing Well in State Enterprise Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, July 17 (Xinhua) -- East China's Shandong Province is
making progress in its enterprise restructuring and now ranks
second in the country in terms of profit.
</P>
<P>
State-owned enterprises earned 6.1 billion yuan in profits last
year, an increase of 21.84 percent over the previous
year. Shandong also reduced the number of enterprises operating at
a loss to 25.41 percent, with total losses worth 2.9 billion yuan,
and the ratio of liability to asset to 66.05 percent.
</P>
<P>
This is encouraging compared to the situation of the country's
stagnant state enterprises, experts said.
</P>
<P>
Shandong selected some 600 major enterprises among its 3,900
state enterprise sector to form enterprise groups, which have
gathered more than 300 billion yuan worth of assets. Fifty-one of
them have begun to try out a modern enterprise system.
</P>
<P>
The province granted special support in technological
improvement projects and loans to eight giant enterprises,
including the Qingdao Haier Group and the Qingdao Brewery Group.
</P>
<P>
It also granted small state businesses greater authority in
operation and management, and introduced the share-holding system
and acquisition. As a result, 75 percent of its 44,000
county-level firms have been reorganized under different systems
and are performing well.
</P>
<P>
The Shouguang Paper-Making Group, which used to lose money, has
developed into a powerhouse in the same sector of the country,
generating more than 100 million yuan in profit and tax annually.
</P>
<P>
The coastal province spent more than 24 billion yuan on 6,000
technological upgrading projects last year, which upon completion
are expected to increase 40 billion yuan in annual industrial
output value and seven billion yuan in profit and tax a year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970717.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ugandans Flee Famine-Stricken Areas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Throngs of residents fled their
home in some areas in the famine-stricken Kumi district, eastern
Uganda, local paper, The Monitor, reported today.
</P>
<P>
Local officials of Ongino, Malera and Kolir sub-counties in
the district told a district council meeting earlier this month
that most local people in their sub-counties abandoned their
homes to seek food in neighboring districts of Mbale, Soroti and
Kapchorwa.
</P>
<P>
Many people sold their properties to save their families, they
added.
</P>
<P>
Kumi is one of the 19 famine-stricken districts of total 45
districts in Uganda.
</P>
<P>
Famine emerged in the season after a prolonged drought. The
east and the north are the most affected areas. The dry season
began in some areas in the east as early as last November.
</P>
<P>
Some witnesses from the east said they did not expect any
decent harvest in this season.
</P>
<P>
Meteorological department said in a statement earlier the dry
season will not end until mid-September. 
</P>
</TEXT>
