<HEADLINE> China Resources To Enter Blue-Chip Index in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 17 (Xinhua) -- China Resources, a leading
China-affiliated conglomerate in Hong Kong, will be added to the
Hang Seng Index, the key indictor of 33 blue chips listed on the
Hong Kong Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
With hefty market capitalization and brisk trading, China
Resources and Cheung Kong Infrastructure (CKI) will replace
Oriental Press Group and Johnson Electric Holdings on July 31,
according to the Hang Seng Index Services (HSI Services).
</P>
<P>
Having expanded its business from trade to property, retail,
port and finance both in Hong Kong and inland areas, China
Resources has a market capitalization of more than 53 billion HK
dollars (6.8 billion US dollars). CKI, which has significant
investments in infrastructure projects in inland provinces, boasts
a market capitalization of nearly 52 billion HK dollars (6.7
billion US dollars).
</P>
<P>
Constituent stocks in the Hang Seng Index accounted for two
thirds of the total market capitalization by the end of June this
year, sources from the HSI Services said. With the reshuffle of
stocks at the end of this month, blue chips will represent 70
percent of the total market capitalization.
</P>
<P>
The Hang Seng Index has already covered two China-affiliated
companies -- Citic Pacific and Guangdong Investment.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
