<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Legislators Pass Bill Freezing Some Pre-handover laws </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, July 17 (Xinhua) -- The legislators of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region (SAR) passed a SAR
government-proposed bill to freeze a number of pre-handover laws
overnight after a seven-hour fierce debate.
</P>
<P>
The 60-seat Provisional Legislative Council (PLC) of the HKSAR
also passed the United Nations Sanctions Bill, which was tabled to
the legislature also by the SAR government.
</P>
<P>
Under the government's original umbrella bill called the
Legislative Provisions (Suspension of Operation) Bill 1997, all
seven ordinances passed by the disbanded previous Legislative
Council at its last session, days before Hong Kong's July 1
handover, were proposed to be frozen.
</P>
<P>
The bill was carried by a vote of 40 to nine overnight at a
full session of the PLC. The laws it suspends mainly concern labor
rights.
</P>
<P>
However, the legislators agreed only to freeze four of the
seven laws. Three other laws the legislators refused to suspend
cover the compensation payments for deafness, the May 1 public
holidays and the protection of the harbor from reclamation.
</P>
<P>
Speaking before the legislators' debate, Chief Secretary for
Administration of the SAR government, Anson Chan Fang On-sang,
stressed that it was necessary to suspend all the seven laws.
</P>
<P>
She said the SAR government was sincere in its desire to study
the laws, more carefully before deciding whether they should be
enacted.
</P>
<P>
"We have given careful consideration to this matter and, as
responsible government, believe it is wrong to repeal these laws,
so we choose to suspend them for further examination instead,"
said the chief secretary.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the SAR government-proposed bill, Chief Executive
of the SAR government Tung Chee Hwa stressed on Wednesday that it
was correct to freeze the labor rights-related laws passed by the
previous Legislative Council.
</P>
<P>
Any reckless passage of these laws, without full consultation
and detailed study, may harm harmonious labor-management relations
in Hong Kong, Tung pointed out.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
