<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Man Catches Rare Disease after Eating Raw Seafood </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 17 (Xinhua) -- A 30-year-old man in Shanghai,
who had eaten some raw seafood before this year's Spring Festival,
is suffering from a rare parasitic disease.
</P>
<P>
The man, surnamed Wu, discovered a red lump on his chest
several days after he ate the seafood. The lump grew and other
lumps formed on his hands, arms and neck, which were swollen,
itchy, and painful.
</P>
<P>
Doctors found it difficult to control the spreading disease,
which was caused by gnathostoma, a type of parasite in sea animals.
</P>
<P>
Experts at the Shanghai Parasite Institute said that the larva
of gnathostoma usually grow in the bodies of fish, frogs and
snakes, while the adults live in the stomachs, esophagus and
kidneys of human beings.
</P>
<P>
After entering a human body, the worm will move through the
body, causing lumps and inflammation of the skin. This can result
in massive bleeding and tissue damage, and when it enters the
internal organs, even death, the experts said. Only about a dozen
cases of the disease have been reported in China in the past 80
years.
</P>
<P>
They suggested people eat cooked seafood instead of raw to
prevent parasite diseases.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
