<HEADLINE> Clinton Endorses Efforts to Protect Kids From Internet Smut </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 16 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
today backed private-sector efforts to protect children from
Internet smut, after his bid for legal limits on Internet was
rejected by the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
Clinton and Vice President Al Gore met earlier today with
parents groups, lawmakers and industry officials to discuss a new
approach of voluntary cooperation from the television industry in
rating programs to protect children.
</P>
<P>
Last month, the Supreme Court struck down a law banning
indecent material on the Internet as a violation of the First
Amendment. Clinton said he was acting in response to the Supreme
Court decision.
</P>
<P>
Following his meeting with industry leaders, Clinton praised
the Microsoft and Netscape companies, which he said are developing
browsers that would let parents block objectionable sites.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said he and industry leaders "have reached a consensus
about how to pave the way to a family-friendly Internet without
paving over the constitutional guarantees of free speech and free
expression."
</P>
<P>
The consensus backed a three-pronged policy, with roles for
industry, government, and parents and educators, Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
In the last three months, the Federal Bureau of Investigation
(FBI) has investigated computer-related exploitation of minors and
established a task force specializing in stopping computer child
pornography.
</P>
<P>
"We simply must not allow pornographers and pedophiles to
exploit this wonderful new medium to abuse our children," Clinton
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
