<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: Southeast Asian Currencies Remain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Southeast Asian currencies remained
unsettled although pressures on the embattled currencies eased
somewhat Wednesday, traders and economists said.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines' peso strengthened slightly against the U.S.
dollar Wednesday, closing at 29.352 and at a weighted average of
29.322 for the day's trading compared with an average of 29.674
the previous day.
</P>
<P>
In Malaysia, the ringgit was confined to a narrow range as
operators took profit after the dollar's failure to break the
2.570 level, as the central bank was believed to have intervened.
</P>
<P>
The Thai baht held above the 30 level against the dollar
despite offshore attempts to push it down.
</P>
<P>
In Indonesia, the rupiah was depressed by ample money market
liquidity and was at 2,457.00 to the dollar against an opening of
2,453.00.
</P>
<P>
As the market stabilizes in the Philippines, the central bank
today lowered its key overnight borrowing rates from 32 percent to
28 percent.
</P>
<P>
The bank doubled the short-term rates to boost the peso when
Thailand instituted a de facto devaluation of the baht two weeks
ago.
</P>
<P>
Although volatility in the region's markets appeared to be
slowing down, traders and economists predicted that Southeast
Asian currencies will remain unsettled until markets fully digest
the policy shifts spawned by Thailand's decision to float the baht
on July 2. The baht has fallen 18 percent in value since then.
</P>
<P>
The Thai government's decision had a grave impact on the
region's currency markets. It forced the Philippine central bank
to trade the peso at "a wider range" last Friday and the peso has
lost 12.5 percent against the dollar in three trading days under
pressure from speculators.
</P>
<P>
In an attempt to make the rupiah less of a target for currency
speculators, Indonesia widened the rupiah's daily trading band to
12 percent from 8 percent last Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian government has also allowed the ringgit to fall.
</P>
<P>
But many of Thailand's woes will continue to buffet neighbors'
currencies, at least in the near future, as the country's
financial trouble is continuing and has an adverse effect on its
economic relations with its neighbors, economists said.
</P>
<P>
Slower economic growth catapulted Thailand into its current
financial trouble. A combination of freewheeling commercial
lending and untrammeled investment by Thai property companies set
the stage. The oversupply of residential and office buildings has
led to defaults on many property loans, which crippled some banks.
</P>
<P>
"My chief worry is that the continued problems in Thailand --
along with posing problems for Thailand, of course -- also make it
difficult to say when things will settle down elsewhere," said
Donald Hanna, regional economist at Goldman Sachs in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Philippine Finance Secretary Roberto de Ocampo said Wednesday
that speculative attacks on the peso can be expected to calm down
over a period of 10 days to two weeks if the past experiences of
markets affected by the Mexico crisis are comparable.
</P>
<P>
But after the de facto devaluation of the Thai baht and the
Philippine peso, currency speculators have turned their attention
to the Malaysian and Indonesian currencies. Any ups and downs in
one currency market will affect others in the region.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, analysts said, it is unlikely for the beleaguered
Southeast Asian currency markets to become quiet in the coming
weeks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970717.0223 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
