<HEADLINE> Thai Hotel Group Gets Tough over Safety Standards </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 17 (Xinhua) -- The Thai Hotels Association (THA)
has got tough and will revoke the memberships of hotels that do
not comply with its newly announced safety rules.
</P>
<P>
New fire safety rules were issued following the Royal Jomtien
Resort blaze in Pattaya last Friday that killed at least 90
people, including foreign tourists.
</P>
<P>
The association, the country's largest grouping of hoteliers
with 350 members nationwide, said it has required its members to
submit hotel building layouts, including the location of safety
equipment, and ensure that sprinklers and emergency flights work
and exits are well lit.
</P>
<P>
The association has also reminded its members to conduct
training and fire drills twice yearly in accordance with the law.
</P>
<P>
The Royal Jomtien Resort fire substantially hurt Thailand's
tourism image both locally and internationally.
</P>
<P>
The association hopes to see an influx of foreign tourists in
the second half of the year as a result of the baht devaluation,
but the hotel industry currently also faces a number of problems
with the continuing economic crisis, as well as the immediate
image problem of hotel operators regarding fire safety, according
to THA President Prapansak Pattayanont.  
</P>
</TEXT>
