<HEADLINE> EU Ban on Indian Seafood to Benefit Thai Exporters </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Thailand stands to gain from a
recent decision by the European Union to ban most imports of fresh
shrimp and crab from India.
</P>
<P>
Following the ban, the EU would need to order frozen shrimp
from other sources and Thailand would step in to fill the void,
according to Thai Foreign Trade Department Director General Pracha
Jarutrakulchai.
</P>
<P>
The EU, which imports about 20,000 tons of shrimp annually from
Thailand, is the third largest market for Thai shrimp products
after the United States and Japan.
</P>
<P>
An EU committee banned Indian seafood after finding evidence of
two types of diseases in both fresh and frozen shrimp and crab.
</P>
<P>
If EU members wanted to continue importing Indian products,
they would be forced to pay more for extra inspections.  
</P>
</TEXT>
