<HEADLINE> Cuba Rules out Sabotage As Cause of Air Disaster </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, July 16 (Xinhua) -- The Cuban authorities today ruled
out sabotage as the cause of Friday's air disaster which killed
44 people.
</P>
<P>
The most probable cause of the crash of a Cubana de Aviation
airplane was a mechanical failure which paralyzed the left engine,
a statement issued by the Cuban Civil Aeronautical Institute said.
</P>
<P>
The statement added that no evidence has been found to show
that there was a fire or explosion during the flight which could
have caused the Soviet-made Antonov plane to plummet since it was
in good mechanical shape.
</P>
<P>
The aircraft dived into the sea two minutes after taking off
from the southeastern city of Santiago de Cuba en route to
Havana. Forty-four people, including six Spanish and two Brazilian
tourists, died in the disaster.
</P>
<P>
The institute said that slow speed, low altitude and the
darkness of the night prevented the crew from being able to
maneuver the airplane to avoid the tragedy.
</P>
<P>
The institute pointed out that 22 bodies have been recovered
from the waters and that 21 of them have been identified and will
be handed over to their next-of-kin.
</P>
<P>
The institute also denied a previous statement that the black
box had been located.
</P>
<P>
What was found was a voice recorder that did not contribute any
useful information to the investigation of the air disaster, the
institute said.
</P>
<P>
Of the people aboard the aircraft, 39 were passengers and 5
were crew members. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
