<HEADLINE> Panama Canal Revenues Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Revenues from the Panama Canal
toll charges increased by 1.5 percent during the first nine months
of the 1997 fiscal year to 374 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Alberto Aleman, administrator of the Panama Canal Commission,
said today that the total earnings in the 1996 fiscal year reached
462 million dollars, the highest in the 82 years of the canal's
history.
</P>
<P>
The passage of ships during the same period decreased by 4.5
percent while the net tonnage of the Panama Canal's universal
tonnage system was down 3.9 percent, Aleman said at the board of
directors of the Canal Commission, consisting of five Panamanians
and four U.S. citizens.
</P>
<P>
The members of the board of directors adopted a proposal made
by a canal transition committee to re-examine and modify the
vision, strategy, objectives and values of the organization.
</P>
<P>
They agreed with the Commission of the Universal Congress of
the Panama Canal to hold a meeting in September here.
</P>
<P>
The board of directors approved Panamanian President Ernesto
Perez Balladares' designation of Jorge Ritter as the first
chairman of the board of directors of the new Panama Canal
Authority, which will replace the commission in 1999. 
</P>
