<HEADLINE> Ukrainian Government Promises to Repay Wages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, July 16 (Xinhua) -- The Ukrainian government has vowed to
pay off all back wages by November 1 if it can secure sufficient
foreign loans and financial assistance.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Igor Mituikov told parliamewnt in a recent
report on wage arrears:"I am sure that if the cabinet receives all
the foreign loans it has expected, all back wages will be paid off.
</P>
<P>
"Current budget revenues are sufficient to pay current wages,
but not enough to pay off back wages."
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Valery Pustovoitenko, who has been nominated by
President Leonid Kuchma as the new prime minister, said he would
take charge of matters concerning the payment of back wages and
pensions if appointed.
</P>
<P>
Before a vote on his candidacy in the parliament, he said
ensuring timely pay and pensions would constitute a major task of
the government.
</P>
<P>
Indicating that the cabinet was seeking credit from sources
other than the International Monetary Fund (IMF), Mituikov said
negotiations were underway with a number of foreign lenders.
</P>
<P>
"Now that the 1997 budget has been approved, we can borrow
money at lower interest rates, and be independent of international
financial institutions," he said.
</P>
<P>
By most accounts, Ukraine and the IMF have not reached an
agreement on a 2.5 billion U.S. dollar loan yet. The back wages
crisis is at the center of the macroeconomic mess that the IMF
insists Ukraine must clean up.
</P>
<P>
State enterprises owed employees 3.5 billion hryvnas (1.9
billion dollars) in back wages as of July 1, while state-financed
organizations owed 1.75 billion hryvnas (950 million dollars), and
the state owed pensioners 1.47 billion hryvnas (800 million
dollars), according to Mituikov. 
</P>
</TEXT>
