<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cuba, U.S. Begin Migration Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Cuban and U.S. government
representatives began the 7th round of closed-door talks on
migration today in New York, a Cuban diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
The talks were attended by the Cuban delegation headed by
Ricardo Alarcon, President of the National Assembly of the
People's Power, and the U.S. delegation led by John Hamilton,
Under Secretary of State for Central America and the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
Participants will renew the agreements on migration existed
between the two sides and reaffirm their pledge to move towards a
definitive agreement, the diplomatic source said.
</P>
<P>
The travel restrictions imposed upon Cubans by the United
States and the extradition of those allegedly responsible for the
hijacking of two Cuban aircrafts will also be discussed, said the
source.
</P>
<P>
The last meeting between the two sides was held on December
4-5, 1996 in Havana.
</P>
<P>
On September 9, 1994, Cuba and the United States signed a joint
statement on migration, complemented by an agreement signed on May
2, 1995, through which the U.S. government would grant 20,000
visas a year to Cuba and expatriate all illegal Cuban emigrants in
the United States.
</P>
<P>
Since then, more than 680 illegal Cuban emigrants have been
turned over to the Cuban authorities.
</P>
<P>
Cuba signed its first agreement on migration with the United
States in 1984 and the second in November 1987. 
</P>
</TEXT>
