<HEADLINE> Brazil Rules out Devaluation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Brazilian Central Bank
Chairman Gustavo Loyola today ruled out any adjustment in the
exchange rate of the Brazilian currency, the real, to the
U.S. dollar in the near future.
</P>
<P>
There were no reasons for altering the exchange rate following
the recent drops in the Brazilian stock market, Loyola said.
Decreases in Brazilian stock exchanges were normal, he added.
</P>
<P>
Stock prices throughout Latin America nose-dived as investors
feared that currency troubles in Asia would spread and jeopardize
the region's economic stability.
</P>
<P>
Experts attributed the 9.4 percent and 7.7 percent drops in the
Sao Paulo and Rio exchanges to the financial crises in several
southeast Asian countries. 
</P>
