<HEADLINE> Russia Remains Opposed to NATO Expansion, FM Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Russian Foreign Minister Yevgeny
Primakov said today Russia remains opposed to NATO's eastward
expansion and this position will not change.
</P>
<P>
"Russia will not change its stand on opposing NATO's eastward
expansion," Primakov told visiting journalists from leading
Japanese newspapers.
</P>
<P>
At a summit in Madrid earlier this month, NATO invited Poland,
Hungary and the Czech Republic to join the military alliance. The
three countries hope to become NATO's new members in 1999.
</P>
<P>
He refuted the notion that there exist direct links between
Russia's active diplomacy in the East and NATO's enlargement.
</P>
<P>
Russia's diplomacy should be multilateral because a multi-polar
world is being shaped, Primakov said.
</P>
<P>
On Russian-Chinese relations, the Itar-Tass agency quoted
Primakov as saying that Russia does not think that China is
threatening world peace and stability.
</P>
<P>
The resolution of the Russian-Chinese border issue, especially
the completion of frontier demarcation by the end of the year,
will provide a good example for other countries to follow, he said.
</P>
<P>
On the situation of the Korean peninsula, Primakov said that
Russia and Japan have agreed to do their best to support the
dialogue "2+2" (South Korea, the Democratic People's Republic of
Korea, China and the United States) to resolve the problem of the
Korean peninsula, and not to obstruct the dialogue.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that Russia and Japan will participate in the
talks under certain circumstances. "Russia hopes to keep a sound
relationship with the DPRK," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
