<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Signs Decrees on Armed Forces Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
today signed decrees to reorganize and reform the Russian armed
forces, the Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Under the decrees, the total of Russian armed forces would be
cut by half a million to 1.2 million servicemen.
</P>
<P>
Explaining to the press, Yeltsin said that the strategic
missile forces, the military space forces and the anti-aircraft
missile forces would be merged into the "missile forces".
</P>
<P>
The air force and air defense forces would also be merged.
</P>
<P>
Under the decree, he added, the general headquarters of the
army would be trimmed while spendings by the offices in the
defense ministry will not exceed one percent of the ministry's
budget.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin made these remarks after he met Prime Minister Viktor
Chernomyrdin at Karelia, north of Russia, where he is on holiday.
</P>
</TEXT>
