<HEADLINE> First Silk World Maps Published in Shanghai </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai has published a
series of world maps made of silk, which have been listed in the
Guinness Book of World Records.
</P>
<P>
The manufacturer, the Shanghai No. 7 Silk Printing Co. Ltd.,
said that following in the footsteps of the world maps are silk
Chinese maps. Both are printed on 1.04 meter long and 0.73 meter
wide pieces of silk.
</P>
<P>
Printing experts believe that the unique material, accurate
printing and bright colors contribute to the beauty and collection
value of the silk maps.
</P>
<P>
The manufacturer said they printed 5,000 copies of the 1997
editions of the World Map and the Chinese Map, which are now on
sale.
</P>
<P>
They also produced 200 copies each of the 1990 edition of the
World Map and the 1996 Chinese Map to be sold at auction. On the
1990 World Map, the Soviet Union still exists, and on the Chinese
map, the southwest China city of Chongqing has not been upgraded to
a municipality. The printing models have been destroyed.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese Revolutionary History Museum will include copies of
the silk maps in its collection.
</P>
<P>
Before this, a silk road map of Shanghai was presented to Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa
before HK's return on July 1, according to the printer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
