<DOCNO> XIE19970717.0245 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethnic Group Pursues New Life After Shelving Shotguns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Once a hunter, 44-year-old Meng
Shuying, has hung up her shotgun and now works on her farm, which
brought in more than 30,000 yuan (3,700 US dollars) in earnings
last year.
</P>
<P>
One year ago, Meng and the other 7,000 members of China's
least-populated ethnic group, the Oroqens, switched careers in a
government-sponsored move to protect local wildlife.
</P>
<P>
The Oroqens, who have lived in north China's Heilongjiang
Province and the Inner Mongolia Autonomous Region for generations,
are known as the "people of the mountains" who make their living
from hunting in the forests.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, the government banned the killing of wildlife because
of the worsening of the eco-system. Soon, most of the Oroqen
people were channeled into the agricultural sector.
</P>
<P>
According to an official from the Oroqen Autonomous Banner, the
administrative unit at the county level in the Inner Mongolia
Autonomous Region, the Banner in 1996 allocated 300,000 yuan (some
37,500 US dollars) to help the Oroqens better adapt to their new
environment.
</P>
<P>
Banner officials also provided training in agricultural
techniques, information services, new highways and electricity to
the places where the Oroqens live.
</P>
<P>
"Our income is much higher than before," said Meng Shuying, who
is the mother of five.
</P>
<P>
She said that this year she will till more land; She bought a
tractor with a 10,000-yuan government loan last year, reclaimed
some 20 hectares of arable land, and harvested 5,000 kilograms of
soybeans.
</P>
<P>
She said, "You know, the government has substantially raised
grain purchasing prices. So, I am going to reclaim another 25 ha
of farmland this year to increase my family's grain production."
</P>
<P>
According to Meng Songlin, magistrate of the Oroqen Autonomous
Banner, the per capita income of these former hunters last year
increased by more than 50 percent to 1,150 yuan.
</P>
<P>
He said that to help Oroqen people achieve prosperity, the
government has so far spent 40 million yunan building power plants
and roads, and installing telephone sets in three Oroqen villages.
</P>
<P>
Now Oroqen people have 19 trucks, 12 tractors and 23 farm
implements, he said.
</P>
<P>
The change has had other positive outcomes: The Oroqens are now
pursuing better education and medical care. And various electric
appliances, furniture, cosmetics, and fashionable dresses have
become popular among the young people.
</P>
<P>
Since the hunting ban became effective, wild animals have
increased their populations, he said, adding that roe deer, deer
and other animals can been found often along roads in the forest
areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970717.0246 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
