<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuchma Names New Prime Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Ukrainian President Leonid Kuchma on
Wednesday formally named Valery Pustovoitenko as the new prime
minister after the parliament adopted his candidacy by a vote of
226 to 91.
</P>
<P>
Pustovoitenko will replace Pavel Lazarenko, who resigned two
weeks ago for "health reasons."
</P>
<P>
As the seventh prime minister in Ukraine's six-year
independence, and the fourth since Kuchma's presidency began in
July 1994, Pustovoitenko showed great confidence in the new job.
</P>
<P>
He said:"Frequent change of prime ministers has ignited intense
political fighting in the country. I'm prepared for that.,"
</P>
<P>
He pledged a good relationship between the government and the
parliament, and consultations and discussions with political
parties on social and economic development plans.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to the parliament session, Kuchma said Pustovoitenko
was experienced in production management and administration as he
had worked in the government for four years.
</P>
<P>
Pustovoitenko, 50, has been the minister of cabinet since 1993,
and once held several local positions in the Dnepropetrovsk Oblast
for a number of years.
</P>
<P>
The major task before the new prime minister following his
appointment is to form a new government. This is no easy job as he
has to consider fully the interests of all the political parties
in the parliament while maintaining national benefits as
instructed by Kuchma.
</P>
<P>
Parliament Speaker Alexander Moroz warned Pustovoitenko to
forget his membership in the People's Democratic Party
(PDP). Pustovoitenko, who served as member of both the Political
Committee and Political Executive Committee of the PDP, pledged to
quit his position in the party if necessary.
</P>
<P>
The toughest task for the new prime minister, however, is to
vitalize the nation's stagnant economy, which continues to decline
 -- and has cost the careers of a prime minister and a deputy
prime minister this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
