<HEADLINE> Ribeiro, Sacramento score impressive wins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Fernanda Ribeiro and Carla
Sacramento, both of Portugal, ran the fastest times of the year to
take the 3,000 meters and mile finals respectively at the Nice
Grand Prix on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Ribeiro, the Olympic 10,000 champion, showed her form for next
month's world championships in Athens by running a year's best of
eight minutes 37.15 seconds in the 3,000 meters, beating Kenyan
Sally Barsosio to second.
</P>
<P>
Sacramento clocked in 4:25.00, the best time of the year over
the mile, with Jacinta Muraguri of Kenya finishing second in
4:26.34 ahead of Australian Margaret Crowley in 4:26.47.
</P>
<P>
South African teenager Llewellyn Herbert, who finished with a
silver medal in the world junior championships last year, scored
another impressive early win in the 400 meters hurdles.
</P>
<P>
He outpaced Zambia's Olympic silver medallist Samuel Matete
over the last two hurdles to win in 48.17 seconds with Matete
second in 48.37.
</P>
<P>
European champion Geir Moen of Norway finished his preparations
for Athens with a win in the 200 meters by overtaking 19-year-old
Seun Ogunkoya of Nigeria in the last 30 meters.
</P>
<P>
Moen clocked 20.41, with American Rohsaan Griffin second in
20.50, the same time as Ogunkoya, who was placed third.
</P>
<P>
Other winners included American Kim Batten in the 400 meters
hurdles, Astrid Kumbernuss in the women's shot and Sarka
Kasparkova of the Czech Republic in the women's triple jump.
</P>
</TEXT>
