<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Honduras to Continue Free Trade Talks with Mexico: Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEGUCIGALPA, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Honduras has to continue free
trade negotiations with Mexico, otherwise, the country would
remain at a disadvantageous place in Central America, Economy
Minister Fernando Garcia said today.
</P>
<P>
Mexico and the Central America's Northern Triangle countries --
Guatemala, Honduras and El Salvador -- have been negotiating for a
free trade agreement (FTA) for more than a year.
</P>
<P>
Guatemala and El Salvador will soon sign the agreement with
Mexico and that would produce an economic triangle against
Honduras, Garcia said.
</P>
<P>
He warned that Honduras runs the risk of disappearing from a
trade map of the Central America.
</P>
<P>
"we cannot remain isolated from the Central American trade
system," the economy minister added.
</P>
<P>
A considerable group of Honduran businessmen is opposed to the
signing of an FTA with Mexico. They said they are not ready to
compete with their Mexican counterparts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
