<HEADLINE> Pakistan Businessmen Hail Government's Trade Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's business community
has welcomed the government's new export-oriented trade policy for
the 1997-98 fiscal year announced Wednesday by Commerce Minister
Ishaq Dar.
</P>
<P>
President of the Karachi Chamber of Commerce and Industry
(KCCI) Mian Shahzada Alam termed the new policy as "export
oriented", saying that in the long term it would be helpful for
the country.
</P>
<P>
The KCCI chief welcomed the incentives for the leather industry
by withdrawing five percent customs duty on blue hides and
reducing duty on finishing and patent leather from 45 percent to
15 percent.
</P>
<P>
He said that leather is the second largest exportable item
after textiles and these incentives would help increase the
country's exports.
</P>
<P>
Another Senior KCCI official also welcomed the efforts made by
the government to reduce trade gap and increase exports by 15
percent.
</P>
<P>
He said the value-added sector should be given more incentives
because there is tremendous potential in this sector to increase
exports.  
</P>
</TEXT>
