<DOCNO> XIE19970717.0267 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WTO Director-General Wishes to Have Short and Simple Jubilee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Director-General of the World Trade
Organization (WTO) Renato Ruggiero said here today that he wishes
to keep the 50th anniversary celebration and the ministerial
conference "short and simple".
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a general council meeting, Ruggiero told
participants that "there has not been yet any general debate about
the scope, agenda or other arrangements", except for the agreement
on the dates for the two events, May 18 to 20, 1998 in Geneva, as
announced before.
</P>
<P>
But "the general view appears to be that the two events should
be kept short and simple", he added.
</P>
<P>
Both WTO members and observers will be invited to the two
events, Ruggiero said, while other intergovernmental organizations
and non-governmental organizations (NGOs) could attend meetings
open to the public on a similar basis to the ministerial
conference in Singapore.
</P>
<P>
The occasion of the 50th anniversary of the multilateral
trading system should be used as "an outstanding opportunity to
reaffirm the continuing relevance and value of the system in a
time of rapid economic change, and to renew our commitment to
keeping it effective in the future to the benefit of all its
members", Ruggiero said.
</P>
<P>
Ruggiero agrees with many members that it would be appropriate
if an event of this importance could be attended at a high
political level, saying that "the participation of senior leaders
would be a very valuable endorsement of what the system means to
the world".
</P>
<P>
Many members prefer that the celebration could be on the third
day (May 20) of the ministerial conference.
</P>
<P>
In order to limit the ministerial conference to one and a half
days, Ruggiero said, "Ministers could be invited to submit
speeches in advance for circulation, as it has been done at all
recent ministerial meetings."
</P>
<P>
As preliminary suggestions, a short formal opening session in
the first morning would be followed in the afternoon by an
informal discussion on a first agenda point, which could be
"Review of Implementation"; another informal discussion in the
following morning on a second point, probably "Future Work
Program"; and a formal closing session in the afternoon of the
second day, which would include a summing up by the chairman.
</P>
<P>
Ruggiero hopes that members will put forward more suggestions
before a consensus is reached. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970717.0268 </DOCNO>
