<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Increasing Overseas Investment in South Chinese City </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZHUHAI, July 17 (Xinhua) -- The city of Zhuhai, a special
economic zone in south China's Guangdong Province, attracted more
than 1.5 billion US dollars in overseas investment during the
first half of the year.
</P>
<P>
The figure represented a 66 percent increase from the same
period last year.
</P>
<P>
The majority of the funds came from Hong Kong and Macao, but
funds from Japan, the US, Canada, Australia, and Germany are
increasing. There are more than 50 multinational companies that
have invested in the city, which now has more than 250
overseas-funded projects each with an investment of more than 10
million US dollars. This is a substantial rise from 15 in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Since the 1990s, overseas funds have accounted for half the
investment in large-scale infrastructure projects, helping build
many bridges, harbors, ports, highways, water and power plants,
and telecom facilities.
</P>
<P>
A new 3.72 million-kw power plant, the largest overseas-funded
project in Zhuhai, has used more than 100 million US dollars of
overseas investment so far.
</P>
<P>
By June the city had actually used more than 4.5 billion US
dollars in overseas investment, helping turn it into a major
Chinese producer of cameras, CD players, VCD players, sewing
machines, and instant noodles.
</P>
<P>
And overseas-funded businesses in Zhuhai now account for
three-fifths of its total exports. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970717.0273 </DOCNO>
