<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 10,000-Year-Old Skull Fossil Discovered in Central China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, July 17 (Xinhua) -- A fossilized female skull dating
back to the late Pleistocene Period (10,000 to 50,000 years ago)
has been discovered in the suburbs of Wuhan, the capital of
central China's Hubei Province.
</P>
<P>
Archaeologists agree that the fossil is from a 25- to
35-year-old woman. Li Tianyuan, one of the archaeologists, said
that the discovery is the first for the province, and that the
skull has been named "Hanyang Man."
</P>
<P>
"Hanyang men" lived during the same period as "Upper Cave Man"
of Beijing and "Ziyang Man" of Sichuan, Li explained.
</P>
<P>
The discovery proves that human beings were active in Wuhan at
least 10,000 years ago, he noted. Research to determine the exact
year of the skull will be done by scientists from the Archeology
Department of Beijing University, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970717.0280 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PNG Peace Talks Reported Making Headway </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WELLINGTON, July 17 (Xinhua) -- Representatives from Papua New
Guinea island Bougainville have taken tentative steps toward peace
talks with the government, said a report in the local paper "The
Dominion" today.
</P>
<P>
The representatives are now meeting at a military camp near New
Zealand South Island city of Christchurch. The NZ-brokered meeting
brings together representatives from the major factions involved
in the cooper-rich Bougainville island, including those from the
PNG Bougainville Transitional Government and the rebel
Bougainville Interim Government.
</P>
<P>
Gerard Sinato, Premier of the Bougainville Transitional
Government, was quoted as saying that the two sides in the
conflict are nearly ready to meet representatives of PNG's central
government to negotiate a peace accord.
</P>
<P>
Though agreement might be months or even years away, he said,
"people are understanding one another and we should move forward
and New Zealand will be a power broker."
</P>
<P>
Rejecting reports that his group is pushing for independence or
autonomy from the central government, Sinato said "there is no
support for independence at this stage or autonomy at the moment."
</P>
<P>
The report also said that rebel leader Francis Ona, who is not
present at the meeting, has said from Bougainville that he gives
qualified backing to peace talks but the only acceptable outcome
would be a referendum on independence.
</P>
<P>
But Sinato said the sides at the talks have expressed no
support for independence or autonomy yet.
</P>
<P>
"At this stage they have not come up to any decision. Before
that is reached, later at another place, it will be talked about
with the national government."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
