<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Agencies Support Annan's Reform Proposals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 16 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations agencies
welcomed and voiced full support for the U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan's reform proposals announced before the General
Assembly this morning.
</P>
<P>
The Administrator of the United Nations Development
Program(UNDP)James Gustave Speth described Annan's reform
proposals as far-reaching, saying:" I strongly support the
Secretary-General's initiatives because they will strengthen and
streamline the UN on every front--peace and security, human
rights, development cooperation, humanitarian affairs and economic
and social affairs."
</P>
<P>
"The renewed UN system sought by the Secretary-General will
become both more effective and more efficient," said the
administrator.
</P>
<P>
Mr. Speth said he was looking forward to the speedy
implementation of these reforms on collaboration with other UN
developing Agencies. "The Secretary-General's proposals have taken
the UN a major step forward toward a renewed world organization
that will become a modern and powerful force for realizing the
goal of global human security."
</P>
<P>
Sadik Nafis, Executive Director of the United Nations
Population Fund (UNFPA) warmly welcomed and fully supported the
Secretary-General's reform proposals as they would affect UNFPA,
saying:"They will contribute to a more effective United Nations
presence in developing countries, enhence the coherence and the
impact of United Nations support for the development and encourage
an increased flow of sources for development, both internal and
external."
</P>
<P>
"The proposed reforms will permit the development work of the
United Nations system to be seen as parts of an integrated whole
rather than as the separate efforts of individual funds and
program," said Dr. Sadik.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, United Nations Environment Program
(UNEP)welcomed the Secretary-General's reform proposals, saying
the Secretary-General's assignment of high priority to the
environment agency of the world community would energize a
transformation already underway.
</P>
<P>
"The reforms announced today have taken into account the
outcomes of the Nineteenth Session of UNEP's Governing Council as
well as the recent UN General Assembly's Special Session in New
York," said UNEP.
</P>
<P>
"The full support of the Secretary-General will take us the
next step in achieving coherence within the United Nations system,
resonance with the expectations of civil society and maintenance
of political vitality. His call for integrity, competence and
efficiency in management reform will encourage us in our results
orientation," said UNEP.
</P>
<P>
Carol Bellamy, Executive Director of United Nations Children's
Fund, affirmed support for the Secretary-General's reforms,
saying:"The bold recommendations grow out of a vision of a United
Nations family dedicated to the most effective possible service to
humanity, especially the world's children."
</P>
<P>
"The Secretary-General represented the General Assembly with a
historic document that will help guide the course of the United
Nations and all its parts to the next century. We applaud him for
his courageous and transforming proposals and look forward to the
General Assembly's upcoming discussion and action," said Bellamy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970717.0283 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan's UN Reform Proposals Appreciated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Representatives of
different regions, countries and UN agencies today expressed
appreciation to Secretary-General Kofi Annan's UN reform
proposals.
</P>
<P>
Jacob Wilmot of Ghana, on behalf of the African states, said
that the overall aim of reform was to make the Organization more
efficient, relevant and effective to be able to fulfil better its
core principles and purposes of promoting peace and security,
economic prosperity, social progress, humanitarian assistance and
overall development; and also to deal with current and future
challenges as the international community entered the new
millennium.
</P>
<P>
It was incumbent upon all member states to respond to the
Secretary-General's initiative by providing him with clear and
coherent policy guidance in the implementation of the proposals.
That should also be done in time, in order not to lose the
momentum, he added.
</P>
<P>
Jean-Louis Wolzfeld of Luxembourg, on behalf of the European
Union and 10 other countries, said that reform was not about
cost-cutting, but rather about enabling the United Nations to meet
its responsibilities. Its objective should be to increase the
Organization's unity of purpose, as well as its ability to respond
flexibly. He was fully committed to making the Organization more
in tune with the existing trends in international relations.
</P>
<P>
Sergey Lavrov of Russia, on behalf of the Eastern European
group, said that consideration of the reform proposals would allow
member states to continue their dialogue with the Secretariat. The
reforms' success would depend on the support they received from
member states. No reforms to strengthen the Organization could be
effective without unconditional support by member states. After
the proposals were considered, an appropriate mechanism should be
established to consider them.
</P>
<P>
Representatives on behalf of Asian countries and of the Latin
American and Caribbean group said that the proposals would be
forwarded to the respective capitals for thorough consideration in
addition to expressing appreciation to the proposals.
</P>
<P>
Bill Richardson of the United States said that when the
Secretary-General had announced his initial reform blueprint in
March, the United States had welcomed it wholeheartedly. Today, he
was pleased to see the Secretary-General's carefully considered
"track two" proposals. He pledged the United States' full support
for making the reform process effective.
</P>
<P>
Chiefs of the United Nations Development Program, Environment
Program, Children's Fund and Population Fund also issued
statement, expressing their support for the reform proposals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970717.0284 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IFC Invests in Lebanon's Telecom Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 16 (Xinhua) -- The International Finance
Corporation (IFC) and Societe Generale (SocGen) of France and
Lebanon today finalized the financing of France Telecom Mobiles
Liban (FTML) in Beirut, Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
The financing package consists of a 75 million U.S. dollar IFC
investment and a parallel senior loan of 25 million dollars from
commercial banks in Lebanon. IFC's investment includes a senior
loan of 20 million dollars and a subordinated loan of 10 million
dollars, both for IFC's own account, and a syndicated loan of 45
million dollars for the account of participant banks, jointly
arranged with SocGen. The package will help finance FTML's 190
million dollar expansion of its digital GSM (Global System for
Mobile Communications) network.
</P>
<P>
IFC is a member of the World Bank Group and the largest
multilateral source of equity and loan financing for private
sector projects in developing countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970717.0285 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IDB Approves Financing to Improve Water, Sanitation in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 16 (Xinhua) -- The Inter-American Development
Bank (IDB) today approved a 40 million U.S. dollar loan to Ecuador
to improve the water and sewerage services of the city of
Guayaquil.
</P>
<P>
The program includes the granting of a long-term concession to
the private sector to promote greater efficiencies of these
services and investment in the system.
</P>
<P>
A 19.8 million dollar component of the program will finance
high-priority rehabilitation work to prevent further deterioration
of existing infrastructure in the system.
</P>
<P>
The project will increase the efficiency of Guayaquil's water
supply, improve distribution in marginal neighborhoods, and
upgrade the sewerage system and reduce flooding in the downtown
area.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the IDB loan, local counterpart will fund total
10 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
