<HEADLINE> Top Clinton Legal Advocate Leaving </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Acting Solicitor General Walter
Dellinger announced Wednesday he will return to teach at Duke
University Law School by September 1.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, U.S. Attorney General Janet Reno described
Dellinger as a "splendid public servant."
</P>
<P>
In his announcement, Dellinger says, "I will always be grateful
to the president for giving me the opportunity to serve in the two
most interesting jobs a lawyer could possibly have. And I will
always cherish my friendship with Janet Reno, who has led this
department with great integrity and with an insistence on doing
the right thing every time."
</P>
<P>
Dellinger came to the Justice Department four years ago as
Clinton's nominee for assistant attorney general in charge of the
Office of Legal Counsel. As such, he acted as the administration's
chief source of legal advice.
</P>
<P>
Reno named him acting solicitor general last year, and he
argued the government's cases before the Supreme Court, but the
president did not send him name to the Senate as a permanent
choice.
</P>
<P>
Dellinger still plans to argue for the proposed Food and Drug
Administration regulation of nicotine and tobacco products before
an appellate court on August 11. 
</P>
</TEXT>
