<HEADLINE> Irish PM Ahern Deeply Unhappy about Haughey's Conduct </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Irish Prime Minister Bertie Ahern
said in Dublin today that he was "deeply unhappy" about the
conduct of former Irish prime minister Charlie Haughey, who had
misled a tribunal over receiving a large sum of cash from an Irish
tycoon.
</P>
<P>
Speaking in an interview with Ireland's state radio, Ahern
said: "I am deeply unhappy with what I heard from yesterday. I'm
afraid it revealed standards of conduct that are unacceptable from
one of the most capable leaders this country has seen."
</P>
<P>
This was Ahern's first comment since Haughey, who had been
Irish prime minister between 1979 and 1992, confessed on Tuesday
that he was sorry for previously denying that he had received 1.3
million Irish pounds (about 2 million U.S. dollars) from
businessman Ben Dunne.
</P>
<P>
Ahern noted that he would await the findings of the tribunal
before deciding whether further inquiry was needed into
allegations of corruption in the political establishment.
</P>
<P>
"My government is committed to implementing the (tribunal)
findings and if there are other matters which the tribunal
believes require investigating, if the truthfulness and integrity
don't add up any more, then they'll have to be further
investigated," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
