<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Greece to Implement Austere Fiscal Policy in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, July 16 (Xinhua) -- The Greek government would
implement an austere fiscal policy next year to make preparations
for the country's entry into the European Economic and Monetary
Union (EMU), a Greek government official said here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters, Yiannos Papantoniou, minister of
National Economy and Finance, said that for the Greek economy,
1998 would be "a tough year" because participation in the single
European currency would depend on achieving targets set in the
Greek government's program to converge with other European Union
(EU) countries.
</P>
<P>
The target of the Greek government was to reduce inflation to
below 3.0 percent from the current 5.5 percent and adjust fiscal
policy to strict provisions contained in the convergence program,
he said.
</P>
<P>
The budget deficit, he predicted, would shrink to 4.2 percent
of gross domestic product this year and that economic growth would
accelerate to 3.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The Maastricht criteria cover inflation, the budget deficit and
public debt, as well as interest rates and exchange rate
stability.
</P>
<P>
Greece and Italy are the only two EU members that will not be
able to join the launch of the single currency in 1999 because of
excessive budget deficits, according to a report issued by
European Commission recently.
</P>
<P>
The economy ministry says that Greece will try to meet the
convergence criteria by the end of 1998, one year later than most
EU members. But most analysts agree that Greece is not likely to
do so before 1999 at the earliest.
</P>
<P>
The Greek Prime Minister Costas Simitis says that his country
will definitely qualify by 1999.
</P>
<P>
The EU's leaders will decide in May 1998 which countries will
qualify for participation in the single currency based on their
economic performance in 1997 and whether it can be sustained.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970717.0291 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-07-17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Unemployment Has Peaked, Official Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, July 16 (Xinhua) -- Germany's unemployment has reached
its peak and is likely to average under 4.3 million in 1997,
President of the German Federal Labour Office Bernhard Jagoda said
today.
</P>
<P>
"We are seeing the first signs of stabilization," Jagoda said
in an interview with the German daily Die Welt. But he also
stressed that it was premature to predict when a real upturn in
employment would actually take place.
</P>
<P>
The number of people out of work in Germany reached 4.374
million in June for a rate of 11 percent.
</P>
<P>
The costs induced by the huge unemployment have put a heavy
financial burden on the German government as it is struggling to
cut budget deficit and national debt in a bid to meet the European
Union requirements for joining the planned single European
currency, the Euro.
</P>
<P>
Under a revised budget for 1997, the government plans to spend
149.06 billion marks (85.5 billion U.S. dollars) in payments for
the jobless people this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
